INSERT INTO `sueed_article` VALUES ('1', 'Set in Stone 01', 'What do you do when you write about a certain six thousand year old consultant so much in your letters that it somehow convinces your entire family you\'re not only dating each other, but that you\'re also engaged?\r\n\r\nIn Childe\'s case, the answer is plain and simple: he goes along with it, of course. Absolutely nothing can go wrong if he makes a contract with the God of Contracts, vowing that the two of them will pretend to be lovers for the duration of his family\'s stay in Liyue. Afterwards, they\'ll return as normal and speak no more of this mess. No feelings or complications involved whatsoever.\r\n\r\nContract accepted. A fool-proof plan set in stone. Right?', 'Chapter 1: The Contract\r\n\r\nDearest  Sister,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nI hope you’re all doing well back there. As promised, along with this letter, I’ve sent over a crate full of food and new toys for everyone back home. \r\n\r\nI know you liked the porcelain dolls I sent last time, so I’ve had a custom one made especially for you. Zhongli told me that the dress the doll is wearing is called a qipao, and it’s what a lot of the women here wear too. As well as that, I’ve also bought you a hairpin. If you look closely at your doll, you can see that she’s wearing the same one. Once I’m back home, I’ll be sure to do your hair exactly like that and we can use the hairpin then, okay?\r\n\r\nBy the way, be careful with the second crate; it\'s very heavy. It\'s all books that I thought Anthon would enjoy. Zhongli recommended a bunch of titles and I didn’t know which ones to choose, so I got all of them. There’s also a few books about the traditions of Liyue. I started reading them when I first arrived here, but Zhongli provides so much knowledge that being around him feels like having a tour guide with me at all times. I thought Father might be interested in the books instead; you mentioned before that he’s been asking about Liyue?\r\n\r\nMost of the food I’ve sent are snacks. I think you and Teucer will enjoy the milk candies, but make sure to keep them away from Anthon. We don’t want any more, ah, accidents. The frozen buns are called baozi; Zhongli and I ate a lot of them last night for dinner. Just steam them and they should be fine. I recommend the ones with the pork filling!\r\n\r\nThat should be enough to keep you all satisfied for the meantime. If Father’s headaches return, be sure to tell me so I can get him more medicine. \r\n\r\nTake care, my Princess Tonia, and remember to keep your brothers out of trouble for me. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nYours faithfully, \r\n\r\nYour loyal knight\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nDear Brother, \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nThank you for the doll and the hairpin! I love them! Mother tried to do my hair like the doll’s but we underestimated how elaborate Liyue hairstyles are, and my hair is far too curly and frizzy for it anyway. If only my hair was neat and pretty too... Still, I will treasure this hairpin forever. I’ve never seen anything so beautiful before!\r\n\r\nOh yes, about the milk candies… Anthon managed to eat a few when we weren’t looking. As expected, he spent that whole evening locking himself up in the bathroom. You can imagine how unpleasant that turned out to be for everyone in the household. Might be best if you don’t send those again in the future… However, Teucer and I did enjoy them a lot. \r\n\r\nFather and Anthon loved the books you sent over. I’ve been reading a few as well, especially the ones about Liyue and its traditions. Everything is so different from Snezhnaya that I find myself constantly at awe with every page I read. Not a day goes by where I don’t regret that I didn’t go with Teucer on his mad adventure there. (Just kidding!)\r\n\r\nBy the way, you seem to be mentioning this Mr. Zhongli a lot in your recent letters… I don’t think Teucer mentioned him at all when he was telling us about his visit there. He’s the consultant at the funeral parlour, is he not? You sound as if you’re fond of him a lot, Brother. \r\n\r\nAs always, I hope you are safe during your travels. Please take care of yourself and know that we are always thinking of you wherever you are in this vast world. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAwaiting for more stories of your adventures, \r\n\r\nYour Princess Tonia\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nDear Little Sister,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWhat are you talking about? Your hair is fine as it is. I will not have you slandering your pretty little self in these letters, or anywhere for that matter. Just wait; when I’m back, I’ll style your hair so good that even your dolls will be envious of you. \r\n\r\nOkay, noted. No more sending dairy products back home unless I want to cause another Anthon Accident. Got it. To compensate, I’ve sent over some red bean buns instead. They’re a bit like the baozi I sent you last time, except these are sweet and filled with red bean paste rather than meat. \r\n\r\nI don’t believe Teucer met Zhongli during his impromptu visit here, but yes, he is the consultant at the funeral parlour. We’ve been spending a lot more time together, considering that he seems to be one of the few people here in Liyue who is not wary of my presence. Before you start fretting, it’s only a bunch of gossip and rumours. I’m fine here, and, besides, Zhongli is plenty of company. \r\n\r\nActually, he’s the one who has been showing me around Liyue. As you can imagine, a Snezhnayan in the middle of Liyue is a rare sight, let alone someone from the Fatui, but Zhongli’s vast array of wisdom has ensured that I do not embarrass myself here. Not too much anyway. Although… Speaking of embarrassing myself, your poor older brother still has not mastered the art of the chopsticks. Who’d have thought two pieces of wood would be so hard to control? Zhongli gifted me with this pair of expensive chopsticks that cost far too much Mora, but I’m afraid they’ll be going to waste at this point. \r\n\r\nEven so, I’ve never seen such fancy chopsticks before. They’re patterned with golden carvings of a dragon and a phoenix. I wish I could show you. \r\n\r\nStay safe, Tonia. Tell Teucer to eat his vegetables, and Anthon to stay away from anything that involves milk. Be sure to send my regards to our parents and elder siblings. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nMissing you all, \r\n\r\nYour loyal knight\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nDear Brother,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nForgive me for the tone of this letter, but are you and Mr. Zhongli partners????? As in, are you two together? And are you aware of what he meant when he gave you those chopsticks??? \r\n\r\nI’m sorry for how short this letter is, but Mother is currently beside me demanding answers and the thought of waiting for your reply is just too much to bear. \r\n\r\nWe await your next letter with bated breaths. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWishing you (and Mr. Zhongli!) are well,\r\n\r\nYour Princess Tonia\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nDearest Tonia,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nEh? Of course me and Zhongli are partners. We spend quite a lot of our time together these days too, as I have been dealing with numerous matters here at the Northland Bank. As for the chopsticks, I knew exactly why he decided to give them to me, so there was no way I could refuse them, even if they are unnecessarily expensive. \r\n\r\nI’m confused as to why you and Mother are reacting like this. I thought I mentioned before that Zhongli was my partner?\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nStay safe and well,\r\n\r\nYour loyal knight\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nTo my dearest, UNBELIEVABLY SILLY BROTHER OF ALL TIME,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nHow could you even ask why we are reacting like this?? OF COURSE we would be shocked at the news that you’re suddenly engaged to Mr. Zhongli! We didn’t even know he was your partner! While the whole household is at a loss for words, I can say for certain that we are OVERJOYED with this news!\r\n\r\nWe’re so happy that you’ve found someone, but we never expected you to arrange your marriage so quickly! Mother has been crying for almost an hour—don’t worry though; they’re tears of joy. And shock—mostly joy, I assure you. \r\n\r\nWe can’t wait to meet Mr. Zhongli! Oh, by the way, have you decided on a date for the wedding yet? And are you having it in Liyue or here in Snezhnaya? Or perhaps both???\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nCongratulations and the bestest of best regards to you and Mr. Zhongli,\r\n\r\nYour Princess Tonia\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nPaimon\'s laughter is shrill; the perfect volume of ear-piercing torture for Childe to consider using her for target practice. He refrains his murderous intentions and settles for glaring at her as she continues to cackle like she\'s just heard Teyvat\'s funniest fucking joke.\r\n\r\n“Let me get this straight,” Lumine says. Her impassive face is a complete contrast to Paimon literally rolling around in the air still laughing her head off. “You wrote about Zhongli so much in your letters that it’s somehow led your family to believe you’re engaged to him?”\r\n\r\nChilde groans. What a mess. “I didn’t even write about him that much!”\r\n\r\nThere\'s a blur of white as Paimon swoops over the table, waving the letters at his face. “You literally wrote so much that your sister mentions you talk a lot about him here—”\r\n\r\n“Give me that!” Childe snatches the letters from her grasp. Unfortunately, she flies back to Lumine\'s side before he can even entertain the idea of strangling her. “What I don\'t understand is how they ended up thinking I\'m not only dating Zhongli, but I\'m marrying him?”\r\n\r\nPaimon rolls her eyes. “You said you were partners! You confirmed that you were together!”\r\n\r\n“I meant business partners! Business! Partners!”\r\n\r\nAs he\'s busy wondering how the very foundation of his world is ending, Lumine leans over to his side and frowns at the letters.\r\n\r\n“I remember Zhongli telling me something about traditions in Liyue…” she mumbles. “Something about the bride offering chopsticks to the groom as a dowry.”\r\n\r\nChilde blinks. An image of the ridiculously expensive chopsticks that Zhongli gifted him flashes in his mind. They\'re currently back home, still in their box. Last night, Childe tried using them for dinner, but eating noodles with chopsticks when you\'re already half asleep was impossible so he gave up, ignoring the apparition of Zhongli\'s disappointed face his brain conjured up with.\r\n\r\n“Chop… Chopsticks?”\r\n\r\nLumine nods. “Specifically designed with a dragon and a phoenix.”\r\n\r\nOh no, he thinks as realisation hits him like one of Zhongli\'s oversized meteors. Oh fuck.\r\n\r\n“But… B-But that was just a gift! That I had to pay for! He wasn\'t using them as an offering to propose to me!”\r\n\r\nLumine shrugs and Paimon returns to another one of her cackling fits. Around them, everyone in the tea house is sneaking glances, most likely wondering why this suspicious Fatui man is having a mid-life crisis while a half-sized mascot laughs at him for the twentieth time.\r\n\r\nChilde bangs his head on the table in the hopes that it wakes him up from this nightmare. “He gave me those damn chopsticks so I could learn to use them properly!”\r\n\r\nA hand lightly pats his head. “Just send a letter back and explain the truth,” Lumine says, pulling him up.\r\n\r\nAs much as he hates the thought of ruining whatever fantasy his family has already conjured up, Childe nods. It\'s only been over a week since he sent that letter; surely his family must have calmed down by now? They must know that him and marriage are two things that can\'t be in the same sentence, especially when it involves a six thousand year old god.\r\n\r\n“Yeah, I\'ll have to,” he sighs. “Before my mother convinces herself I\'ve finally decided to settle down and lead a normal, domestic life.”\r\n\r\nPaimon giggles. “You, normal, and domestic are three things that can never co-exist together.”\r\n\r\nFor once, Childe agrees with her.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nThe sun has long set by the time Lumine and Paimon leave him to figure out how he\'s going to fix his mess. He barely pays attention to where he\'s going, mumbling an apology every time he bumps into someone in Feiyun Slope. It\'s especially busy at this time with all the merchants packing up their wares and people rushing back home in time for dinner. Childe\'s stomach rumbles, but he ignores it. Instead, he\'s on his seventh mental draft of the letter he wants to send to his sister.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nDearest Tonia,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nI\'m not getting married, nor am I ever going to get married. Sorry to disappoint you, but—hey, I\'ve bought more kites and dolls for you and the boys. There\'s also a pack of luxury bath soaps for Mother, and more medicine for Father. Now, can we please move on from this?\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nYours faithfully,\r\n\r\nYour very stressed but loyal knight\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nHm. Maybe he needs to sugarcoat that a bit more.\r\n\r\n“Childe?”\r\n\r\nHe stops in his tracks, looking around him until his eyes meet an amber gaze. Zhongli offers him a gentle smile that sends the mental letter in Childe\'s head disintegrating.\r\n\r\n“Xiansheng,” Childe greets. He nods towards the funeral parlour. “Finished with work already?”\r\n\r\nZhongli walks to his side. “Yes. I was just about to get dinner. Would you care to join me?”\r\n\r\nTranslation: Would you care to join me for dinner that you\'ll end up paying for? Still, Childe nods. He is hungry, and saying no to Zhongli is hopeless.\r\n\r\n“Sure, I could do with some food. Wanmin Restaurant?”\r\n\r\nWanmin Restaurant is as busy as ever when they arrive there. Fortunately, Xiangling is on duty and she manages to clear a table for them. Childe reminds himself to give her a hefty tip after their meal.\r\n\r\nAs usual, Zhongli decides what they\'re getting. Childe prides himself in the fact he\'s had dinner with the consultant so many times that he\'s stopped wincing at all the expensive meals he chooses. Nevertheless, while his face is stoic, he still counts every meal in his head and thinks What the fuck. Golden crab, Qingce stir fry, Jueyun chili chicken, jewellery soup, and jade parcels. Oh, and some fried radish and grilled tiger fish on the side. Tsaritsa, is Zhongli planning to feed all of Liyue?\r\n\r\nHe\'ll never understand how the bank still has any money left with the amount of times he\'s directed their bills towards it.\r\n\r\nBy the time all of the food arrives, there\'s hardly any room for it on their small table. Trusty chopsticks in hand, Childe scans the dishes and wonders what he\'ll eat first.\r\n\r\nHe decides on the jade parcels. Not because they look like they\'ll be the easiest to pick up with chopsticks or anything.\r\n\r\nThe two of them fall into comfortable silence until Zhongli swallows what\'s in his mouth and talks about—anything. Every now and again, he\'ll go off into a tangent about what they\'re eating, explaining to Childe how it\'s cooked and prepared, or the whereabouts of its origins. This happens every time they eat together, to the point where Childe\'s brain is filled with all these recipes he wants to cook for his family one day.\r\n\r\nWhile Zhongli is in the middle of another history lesson, Childe sneaks a glance at him. The glow of the lanterns around them brightens the tips of his hair, almost as if the strands are illuminated during the evening. His amber gaze is tinged with a golden hue so bright that it becomes harder and harder for Childe to tear his eyes away before the consultant notices he\'s quite literally oggling him. He forces his gaze down towards Zhongli\'s hands, focusing instead on the delicate hold he has over his chopsticks, nothing like how Childe is currently holding his like... well, like a knife.\r\n\r\nChilde finds himself frowning. Why did Zhongli give him those expensive chopsticks? Is it true that those are sometimes used as a dowry? Does Zhongli even know that?\r\n\r\nWait, of course he does. Zhongli knows everything and anything when it comes to Liyue. Even so, why would he give them to Childe?\r\n\r\n“Xiansheng, I was wondering…” Childe says. “Those chopsticks you gave me...”\r\n\r\nZhongli\'s head turns to him. The piercing gold of his eyes sends all thoughts inside Childe\'s head scampering off.\r\n\r\n“Yes?”\r\n\r\nChilde looks away, scrambling for something, anything to say—anything that doesn\'t involve engagements or dowry offerings. “They were a bit expensive, don\'t you think? And I don\'t even know how to use them properly yet.”\r\n\r\nHe hears Zhongli sighing. “I was under the impression that you were trying to improve.”\r\n\r\n“I am! It\'s just...” Childe stabs his chopstick through a jade parcel. “Difficult.”\r\n\r\nHe\'s just about to shove the parcel into his mouth when Zhongli\'s hand envelops his. Childe freezes. He doesn\'t realise he\'s holding his breath until Zhongli pushes the parcel off the chopstick and guides his hand to pick it up properly. Even through their gloves, Childe can feel how warm Zhongli\'s palm is—or maybe that\'s his entire body about to combust.\r\n\r\n“I thought you were someone who liked to master everything he did not excel in.”\r\n\r\nHe makes the mistake of glancing up. Zhongli is leaning over the table, his ponytail swept over his shoulder and his eyes drowned in Cor Lapis. Childe lets out the breath he\'s been holding just as his brain short circuits and comes out with one thought: Why is Zhongli so pretty?\r\n\r\nHe clears his throat and does the only thing he can do to recover: he shoves the entire parcel into his mouth and almost chokes to death.\r\n\r\nZhongli leans back, his lips tugging up into an amused smile. He calls Xiangling to fetch more water for Childe.\r\n\r\n“I am,” Childe says again, when he\'s finished spluttering for air. “Give me more time.”\r\n\r\nZhongli\'s smile drops slightly and he looks down at the chopsticks in Childe\'s hand.\r\n\r\n“I will wait,” he says.\r\n\r\nChilde curls his lip, pushing the food around on his plate. He didn\'t realise Zhongli was that hung up on him being so shit with using chopsticks.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWhen he returns to his chambers, Childe only has enough energy to change into his evening robes before he collapses into bed. In the back of his mind, he recalls that he should be writing a reply to Tonia—but, fuck, he\'ll do that tomorrow morning. The last thing he remembers is a hazy image of Zhongli sitting across from him, his golden-tinted eyes brighter than any lantern that illuminates Liyue\'s vermilion streets.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nScaramouche is doomed and his life is forfeit in Childe\'s hands. As Childe is about to decapitate the evil midget with his own stupidly, large hat, Scaramouche starts screeching and the whole world shakes.\r\n\r\n“Lord Harbinger! Lord Harbinger!”\r\n\r\nChilde jolts awake. It takes him a few seconds to shake himself out of his dream, cursing the fact he couldn\'t at least finish it before he was rudely woken up. Groaning, he rubs his eyes and scans the room, trying to find the source of the voice.\r\n\r\n“Lord Harbinger!”\r\n\r\nThe door. There\'s someone at the door. And by the sounds of it, they\'re either dying or the world is ending.\r\n\r\n“W… What?” Childe clears his throat, wincing at how husky his voice sounds. “What is it?”\r\n\r\n“It’s your family, sir! One of our men spotted them at the harbour!”\r\n\r\nThat wakes him up. Childe\'s eyes widen and he throws the blankets off him, stumbling for his shoes. “What? Are you serious?”\r\n\r\n“Yes, sir. It seems they have just arrived—”\r\n\r\nChilde is out of the room before the Fatui recruit can take another breath. He trips out of the guest house and ignores the startled shouts from people, probably wondering why in the Abyss he\'s running outside in nothing but his evening robes.\r\n\r\nSeveral thoughts are dashing in his head right now: what the fuck, how the fuck, why the fuck.\r\n\r\nIt\'s got to be a mistake, right? Maybe the Fatui recruit who spotted his family needs glasses and he mistook what he saw. Maybe he was hallucinating. Maybe he was playing around and Childe will have to fight him later for even daring to pull something like this off.\r\n\r\nChilde skids to a stop as soon as he arrives at the harbour, and with that, all of his hopes crumble into ashes. It takes him mere seconds to recognise Tonia\'s curly mane of red hair and the Snezhnayan coats that are far too thick for this kind of weather.\r\n\r\nWHY? he demands to every Archon in existence as his mother turns around, bundled up in several layers of fur, gasping as soon as she sees him. Her pale blonde hair is shorter than he remembers it, yet there\'s no mistaking that it\'s his mother; beautiful and exuberant as always.\r\n\r\nWithin the blink of an eye, Childe is enveloped into a hug that\'s close to breaking his bones and suffocating him in fur. He writhes in her arms, trying to hug his mother back while still demanding WHY to all the existing Archons or godly presence out there.\r\n\r\n“Ajax!” his mother shrieks down his ear. She pulls away and attempts to tidy the mess that\'s his bed hair. After her fourth attempt of trying to flatten a stubborn strand, she gives up and pats his head instead. “Oh my, you’ve gotten so much taller! And so handsome!”\r\n\r\nShe grabs him by the cheeks and turns his face towards his father. Any faster and Childe is certain she would have snapped his neck off.\r\n\r\n“Dear, look at him! Our baby is all grown up!”\r\n\r\nThe \'baby\' in question is now dying from embarrassment. Childe is all too aware of everyone watching them. It doesn\'t help that the harbour is one of the busiest places here in Liyue. From the corner of his eyes, he can see a few Fatui recruits uselessly standing in the distance. They\'re all looking at each other, unsure as to what they can do in a situation like this.\r\n\r\n“Ajax, it\'s good to see you,” his father says. He lays a hand on Childe\'s shoulder and smiles at him. The last time Childe saw his father, his hair was still a full head of red; now, there are also streaks of silver and white. “When Tonia told us you were getting married, your mother didn’t hesitate to find the earliest ship that would take us to Liyue.”\r\n\r\nTonia jumps into his field of vision. Her hair is as wild and untamed as ever, but she\'s no longer the tiny girl with missing front teeth in his memories. When she grins at him, her teeth are straight and dimples press into her freckled cheeks.\r\n\r\n“Brother, I tried to stop them but Mother was so excited!” she says, giggling. “She wouldn’t listen to me!”\r\n\r\nThere\'s a tug at his sleeve and he looks down to find Anthon fixing his wonky glasses.\r\n\r\n“If Teucer can go to Liyue all by himself, then why can’t we?” he says, tugging on Childe\'s sleeve again. “Brother, can you show me to the bookstore? I saved up lots of Mora to buy some—”\r\n\r\nSomeone tugs at his other sleeve. Teucer pops into view, scowling at Anthon.\r\n\r\n“Who wants to go to some boring old bookstore?” He pulls Childe\'s arm, attempting to move him to his side. “Brother, can you show me to the toy factory again? I want to see Mr. Cyclops and all his friends!”\r\n\r\nAnthon huffs, pulling at Childe\'s other arm. Childe can only sigh as his two brothers engage in a tug of war.\r\n\r\n“You already went to the toy factory last time! You don’t need to go there again!”\r\n\r\nTheir mother laughs. She pries her sons\' grip off Childe and gathers them into her arms, ruffling both of their hair until they protest.\r\n\r\n“Now, now, boys. Let’s all calm down and let your poor brother take all of this in. Besides, we can save all the shopping and tourism for another day.” She beams at Childe. “First, we must meet this Mr. Zhongli. Where is he?”\r\n\r\nChilde sincerely hopes he\'s not grimacing. “Ah. Yes. About that—”\r\n\r\n“I’m still in shock that you’ve found someone, let alone decided to get married,” his father says with so much awe in his eyes that you\'d think he\'d just caught Leviathan during their fishing trips. “Our reckless, trouble maker settling down at last…”\r\n\r\n“Wait, that’s actually—”\r\n\r\nHis words are, once again, interrupted as his mother envelops him into another bone-crushing embrace. “Oh, Ajax. You have no idea how delighted we are with this news. As soon as I read your letter, I burst into tears!”\r\n\r\nTonia muffles her laughter with her hand, nodding. “She actually did. She cried for an hour.”\r\n\r\n“And then she cried some more the next morning when she reread your letter,” Teucer adds.\r\n\r\nAt this rate, it sounds like his mother is going to start crying now.\r\n\r\n“It\'s just everything I could ever want for you, Ajax! I was always worried that you were lonely and that you missed home… I\'m just glad you have someone who makes you happy.” His mother sniffs, and Childe prays to the heavens that she won\'t start sobbing in the middle of the harbour. “I think I may start crying again.”\r\n\r\nAnthon rolls his eyes. “Mother, please don\'t. You\'ll set Father off as well.”\r\n\r\nTo Childe\'s horror, their father dabs at the corner of his eyes and starts sniffing.\r\n\r\nChilde sighs. He steps back and takes several deep breaths, then plasters on a smile that could make even the most skilled actors proud of him.\r\n\r\n“Let’s… go back to my place. All of you must be so tired,” he says, still grinning. “I’ll make us some breakfast and… I’ll explain everything.”\r\n\r\nThis is his last hope. If he can get his family to calm down and listen to him for a moment, then he can tell them this is all... one... big... misunderstanding.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n“What do you mean you didn’t tell your family the truth in the end?!” Lumine says, and Childe immediately knows it\'s bad when even Lumine is judging him along with Paimon.\r\n\r\nHe lets his head fall into his hands. “I couldn’t do it! I couldn’t look at my mother in the eye and tell her! She was so happy! I can’t ruin that!”\r\n\r\nHe tried. He really did. He went through a dozen speeches in his head while cooking breakfast, but all of it faded away the moment he looked at his mother\'s face. And then all further attempts were thwarted when he looked at the rest of his family and saw they all had similar expressions. Was him getting married that big of a deal?\r\n\r\n“So what? You’re just going to let them believe you and Zhongli are getting married?” Paimon asks. “Paimon thought Teucer believing you were a toy seller was ridiculous, but this is on another level! There’s no way you can pull this off!”\r\n\r\nChilde groans. “I managed to calm them down a bit and tell them the wedding wasn’t for certain yet… Now, they just think Zhongli and I are dating but that we’re considering getting married in the future.”\r\n\r\nLumine\'s eyebrows knit together. She sighs, reaching for her tea. Childe wonders if it\'s too early to start drinking alcohol when noon has barely finished, but damn he needs a drink right now.\r\n\r\n“That’s hardly any better,” Lumine says. “Does Zhongli even know anything about this?”\r\n\r\nChilde\'s silence is enough of an answer.\r\n\r\n“You haven’t told him? You have to tell him!” Paimon demands, swooping dangerously close to his face. “Zhongli is such a blockhead that he’ll probably expose all your lies within seconds if your family ever talk to him!”\r\n\r\nChilde swats her away. “I was getting to that! I’m just… wondering how I can convince him to go along with this.”\r\n\r\nLumine shakes her head. “I can’t believe you’re actually doing this.”\r\n\r\n“What else can I do?”\r\n\r\n“I don’t know; maybe tell them the truth? Say it’s all a misunderstanding?” Lumine raises an eyebrow. “Like what most people would do?”\r\n\r\nChilde ignores the sass in her voice. That, coupled with Paimon\'s shrieking is unbearable in the current state of his head right now.\r\n\r\n“No, no, I can’t. My family travelled all the way here just because they were so excited to see me tying the knot. My mother was so happy she started crying! And my father! The only time I ever saw him cry was when we caught a fish that was larger than our house…”\r\n\r\nPaimon jerks back. “First of all, how big are the fish in Snezhnaya…”\r\n\r\nLumine waves her off with a hand. “That\'s not important. How long are your family staying here for anyway?”\r\n\r\nChilde taps on the table, trying to remember. “Two weeks, I think?”\r\n\r\n“So, you’re going to pretend to date Zhongli for two weeks… And then what?” Paimon asks.\r\n\r\n“When they get back to Snezhnaya, I can just say the relationship didn’t work out and that we broke up… Maybe we can even act out an argument before they leave or something. Make it more believable.”\r\n\r\nLumine holds her forehead and mumbles something under her breath. Childe doesn\'t need to hear it to know she\'s currently judging his life choices.\r\n\r\n“Wouldn’t that upset them anyway?” she slowly says. “Why go through all the trouble of pretending to date Zhongli to not upset them, when you’re only going to do it in the end?”\r\n\r\n“They already believe I’m dating him! I can’t just take it back!”\r\n\r\nPaimon throws her arms in the air. “Because you made them believe it! You’re so stupid!”\r\n\r\n“Shut up! This is the only way forward now!”\r\n\r\nLumine drinks the rest of her tea, the action far too calm for the raging chaos storming through Childe\'s life. “How are you even going to keep your Fatui business away from your family now that they\'re here?”\r\n\r\nHe wishes she didn\'t have to remind him. Thinking about that on top of the Zhongli thing is enough to send him mad. “Everyone apart from Teucer knows I work for the Tsaritsa, so they\'re aware they have to keep it a secret... I\'ll just... have to be extra careful.”\r\n\r\nLumine\'s eyes hold nothing but pity for him. “Of course, there\'s also the matter of whether Zhongli will even agree to this.”\r\n\r\nChilde turns towards the direction of the funeral parlour, easily spotting its balcony from where he\'s sat in the tea house.\r\n\r\n“He will,” he says. “I know he will.”\r\n\r\nIf not... Well, he hopes Wangsheng Funeral Parlour is empty today because he might just resort to begging on his knees.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAs luck would have it, the funeral parlour is fairly empty today. Childe follows the scent of incense, so strong he knows it\'ll cling onto him even when he\'s left. He\'s only been to the parlour a few times, and while he\'s not the sort to be easily frightened, he can\'t help but feel there are eyes following him everywhere.\r\n\r\nHe finds Zhongli all alone, huddled over a desk. Childe announces his presence with a light cough, although he\'s sure Zhongli already knew he was there. Don\'t gods have heightened senses or something? Well, in Zhongli\'s case, ex-god.\r\n\r\nZhongli glances up, setting aside his brush. Out of curiosity, Childe looks at what he was writing; the language is foreign and he hasn\'t stayed in Liyue long enough to recognise any of its characters.\r\n\r\n“Childe, this is a surprise,” Zhongli says, motioning towards the seat opposite him. “What brings you here?”\r\n\r\nChilde sits down, mentally flickering through all of the speeches he\'s made this afternoon. As the God of Contracts, Zhongli is used to people asking for help. It\'ll be best if Childe gets down to the point.\r\n\r\n“Xiansheng, sorry to disturb you, but I… I need a favour.”\r\n\r\nZhongli raises an eyebrow, but nevertheless remains silent, waiting for him to elaborate.\r\n\r\nChilde takes a deep breath. “I need you to date me.”\r\n\r\nZhongli blinks.  “Excuse me?”\r\n\r\nShit. “I-I mean—I need you to pretend to date me.” Childe forces out a laugh that sounds more like a cry for help. “Long story short, my family may have misunderstood my letters and they’re now convinced we’re dating. Hilarious, right?”\r\n\r\nHe laughs again, and it\'s the most painful five seconds of his short, pathetic life.\r\n\r\nDoesn\'t help that Zhongli isn\'t laughing. He\'s staring at Childe as if he\'s grown a second head.\r\n\r\nChilde winces. He\'s already started, so he may as well throw away what little is left of his dignity and keep going.\r\n\r\n“They decided to surprise me with a visit out of nowhere. They’re in Liyue for the next two weeks, and I was hoping that you’d… well, I was hoping you’d go along with the act and pretend to date me.”\r\n\r\nZhongli\'s face finally shows a sliver of emotion. He frowns. Childe doesn\'t think that\'s a good reaction.\r\n\r\n“An... act?”\r\n\r\nChilde quickly nods. “Of course, just an act. Once my family leaves, I can tell them we broke up. I know this is so sudden and you’re probably really confused, but I just need you to keep up the lie while they’re here.” He sighs, suddenly remembering one of his mother\'s demands. “They want to meet you as well…”\r\n\r\nFor the longest time, Zhongli is quiet. He turns his head away, staring off into the distance while Childe waits in excruciating silence. Is he angry? Annoyed? Because if so, then what are the chances that he\'s pissed off enough to summon a meteor here and now?\r\n\r\nChilde thinks he\'s losing it. The mental image of Zhongli summoning a meteor right in the middle of Feiyun Slope is both hilarious and concerning.\r\n\r\nThe sound of Zhongli\'s clothes rustling pulls Childe away from his thoughts. When he focuses back on Zhongli, he finds that the ex-Archon is still not staring in his direction. He has his gaze fixed on the table.\r\n\r\n“To summarize, you wish for me to pretend that we are lovers for the duration of your family’s visit. As soon as they leave, the act is no longer needed.”\r\n\r\nIt\'s difficult to determine what Zhongli is thinking right now. His voice is the same as always, soothing and polite, although he\'s talking so slow that Childe worries he\'s greatly offended him.\r\n\r\n“I know this is a lot to ask for, but it’s only for two weeks,” he reassures. “Once that’s over, we can quit the act and that’s it.”\r\n\r\nZhongli slowly nods. He\'s still not looking at Childe and it\'s driving him insane. To make things worse, Zhongli decides now is the best time to pour himself some tea.\r\n\r\nChilde has never been patient, ever, in his life. So, of course, he talks some more in the hopes that it will finally make the older man look at him.\r\n\r\n“Xiansheng, I’m sorry if this makes you uncomfortable, but I promise it’s just for two weeks. I wouldn’t be asking this of you if I wasn’t desperate.” He pauses, suddenly hit with a brilliant idea. “How about this: we can make it into a contract?”\r\n\r\nAs expected, Zhongli finally looks up.\r\n\r\n“A contract?”\r\n\r\nFor a brief second, his eyes are wide and Childe swears the grip he has around his tea cup tightens. As soon as he blinks, it\'s gone and Zhongli\'s face is back to being as cold as stone.\r\n\r\n“Yeah.” Childe nods. “For two weeks, we’ll pretend to be lovers in front of my family, but I promise that as soon as those two weeks are over, the act ends there and we can go back to how things used to be. No feelings or complications. Is that okay? In return, I can buy you anything you—”\r\n\r\nZhongli shakes his head. “I am asking for nothing in return.”\r\n\r\n“Are you sure? I know I’m asking a lot from you so—”\r\n\r\n“I am certain.”\r\n\r\nZhongli sits up straighter and stares at Childe directly. The room they\'re in is so dimly lit that the golden flecks in Zhongli\'s eyes are practically incandescent amidst the shadows. In that moment, Childe has the distinct feeling he\'s no longer looking at Zhongli, but the God of Contracts—and here he is, binding himself to one of his contracts.\r\n\r\n“Very well. A maximum period of two weeks to convince your family that we are lovers, and after that, we will resume our relationship prior to this as normal. No feelings or complications will be involved whatsoever. Those are the conditions of this contract?”\r\n\r\nVaguely, Childe recalls that Zhongli does not hesitate to eradicate those who break his contracts. One part of his brain, albeit a very small one, tells him he should probably be careful with this.\r\n\r\nOf course, he ignores that voice in his head. Besides, what can go wrong? The conditions are that they\'ll only be pretending for two weeks, and after that, everything will return back to normal. That\'s what Childe wants, and he knows the same must go for Zhongli.\r\n\r\n“Right,” he agrees. “Those are the conditions of this contract.”\r\n\r\nZhongli inhales a deep breath, setting his tea cup down. “Then it is agreed upon. I will place my trust on you and this contract between us.” Golden eyes narrow at him. “Betray it, and you taint my blood.”\r\n\r\nChilde laughs. He leans forward to shake the ex-Archon\'s hand.\r\n\r\n“Contract accepted,” Childe says, and just like that, everything is set in stone.', 'set_in_stone.jpg', '2021-04-10 07:12:50.285735', '2021-04-26 10:15:17.611594', '0', '1', 'set_in_stone_01', '1', '2', 'Set in Stone');
INSERT INTO `sueed_article` VALUES ('2', 'Set in Stone 02', 'the same with 01', 'Chapter 2: Just Practice\r\n\r\nThe weight of accepting Zhongli’s contract is instantaneous. Childe looks down at their hands, still locked in a handshake that he’s slowly realising has lasted far too long, and thinks ‘Now what?’\r\n\r\nFor starters, it would be a good idea to let go of Zhongli. Now. \r\n\r\nChilde pulls away, watching as Zhongli relaxes back into his chair as if he hasn’t just agreed to what may be one of Childe’s dumbest plans in his life so far. Now that Zhongli has agreed to it, Childe is at a loss as to what happens next. He didn’t actually think it would be that easy to get the Archon to say yes. Part of him expected (and hoped) to fight Zhongli, maybe beat him into submission until he had no choice but to accept Childe’s crazy plan. \r\n\r\nOf course, Childe is aware Zhongli wouldn’t have gone down without a fight… That’s what makes it sound more alluring… Damn, he really should have challenged him to a duel first instead of proposing a contract. \r\n\r\n“You mentioned your family wishes to meet me?”\r\n\r\nChilde snaps away from his thoughts. He mentally grimaces at the memory of his mother pretty much demanding to meet Zhongli as soon as possible.\r\n\r\n“Yeah. Are you okay spending dinner with us at my place tomorrow?”\r\n\r\nZhongli nods. “I can do that.”\r\n\r\nGreat. Approximately twenty-four hours until he meets his doom. \r\n\r\n“We must ensure that we act like lovers in front of them,” Zhongli tells him. \r\n\r\n“Right,” Childe agrees. \r\n\r\nLovers. What a strange concept. He’s never bothered with a serious relationship before; being one of the Tsaritsa’s Harbingers doesn’t exactly give one much time to pursue anything outside of the occasional alcohol-induced one night stand. Even then, sex and romance are two completely different things. He’s always regarded sex as another form of battle; depending on who you’re with, it can be exhilarating, it can be boring.\r\n\r\nAs for romance, he’s completely stumped with that one. \r\n\r\n“So, holding hands and pretending to be madly in love and all that,” Childe suggests like the expert he clearly is. \r\n\r\nZhongli frowns. “Lovers do more than just hold hands.”\r\n\r\nChilde’s eyes flicker to Zhongli’s lips before he realises what he’s doing. He quickly looks away, but the damage is done. Now his brain is populated with images of kissing the ex-Archon; an image he\'d never thought of before, although… Well, he’s not against it. They’ll have to do it at some point if they want to make this believable, won’t they?\r\n\r\n“I know that,” he mumbles. “My family’s already on board with the idea that we’re considering engagement at this point, so I don’t think they need much convincing.”\r\n\r\nHe says it to reassure both Zhongli and his sanity, but it only makes the ex-Archon’s frown deepen. \r\n\r\n“If that’s the case, then would they not be suspicious if our actions do not match that?” Zhongli asks. \r\n\r\nChilde shrugs. “I suppose you’re right… Are you okay with, uh, kissing and stuff?” \r\n\r\nEloquently put, Childe, the asshole part of his brain tells him. Kissing and stuff. He’s pretty sure they won’t need to do anything beyond kissing, unless this contract is really set out on making him lose what little sanity he has left. \r\n\r\nZhongli doesn’t even look fazed at all. “I have accepted a contract with you,” he says, calm as ever. “I will do anything that’s required of me.”\r\n\r\nNot really the best thing to be saying when Childe’s brain is still ambushing him with images that are gradually becoming more and more inappropriate. \r\n\r\n“Okay. That’s… That’s cool.”\r\n\r\nTo distract himself from his increasingly unholy thoughts, he stands up and pretends to be interested in one of the scrolls hanging on the wall. He can’t understand a single character that’s written on it and it doesn’t help he can feel Zhongli’s eyes piercing straight through his back. \r\n\r\n“We’ll need to decide on our history.”\r\n\r\n“History?” Childe looks over his shoulder. Zhongli has returned to filling in the paperwork he’d been doing before he arrived here. He’d almost forgotten he barged in here while Zhongli was working. Deciding it’d be best to wait, Childe folds his arms and leans on the table behind him—\r\n\r\nIt wobbles. He regains his balance as quickly as he can and throws his hands out to steady the table. When he turns around, he sees that it’s more of a counter with a white sheet draped above, hiding whatever is below it. He hears Zhongli let out an unimpressed sigh just as something slides out from under, landing by Childe’s feet.\r\n\r\nAn arm. It’s an arm cleanly sliced from someone’s torso. \r\n\r\nChilde whistles, unable to help himself. He bends down to pick it up, intending to shove it back under the covers until his curiosity gets the better of him. Lifting the corners of the sheet, he inspects the body underneath and raises his eyebrows at the neat precision of the wound. He’s never seen such a clean cut before.\r\n\r\n“Damn,” he says, impressed. “Whoever killed them must have had an amazing blade. A cut this neat would have felt like slicing into butter.”\r\n\r\nZhongli coughs. “Childe. Please leave the corpse alone.”\r\n\r\n“Sorry,” Childe says, much like a kid reprimanded by their parents. He attempts to move the arm back to where it was, but it tumbles down on the floor with a loud thud. “Drat.\"\r\n\r\nZhongli releases another long suffering sigh. He rises from his chair and slides past Childe, rearranging the corpse back to its original state and covering it with the sheet. \r\n\r\nIf Childe’s mother ever asks him what they did for their first date, Childe can tell her they spent it surrounded by the romantic atmosphere of mutilated corpses. \r\n\r\n“Let us discuss this elsewhere,” Zhongli says.\r\n\r\nHe leaves no room for argument and abandons Childe in the parlour. The warmth of Liyue’s summer breeze hits Childe as soon as he jogs outside, catching up to the older man. At this time, the harbour is at its busiest, with the voices of merchants drowning each other out in an endless competition to see who can lure their next customer first. \r\n\r\nThis is also the most dangerous time for someone like Zhongli to be walking about. \r\n\r\nAs Childe expected, Zhongli is detained by at least three merchants who convince him to buy their overpriced goods and—to no one’s surprise—Childe is the one who pays. By the time the fourth merchant attempts to call out to Zhongli, Childe literally has to grab the older man’s wrist and drag him away. \r\n\r\nNote to self: Avoid walking around Liyue with Zhongli during business hours. Not because losing Mora is an issue, but because you will literally spend almost two hours waiting for him to decide which shiny object he should add to his collection. \r\n\r\nTwo hours later, they are finally seated in Wanmin Restaurant. It’s a good thing the only people waiting for Zhongli at the funeral parlour are, well, dead because Childe is pretty sure disappearing for that long during your shift is highly frowned upon. \r\n\r\n“As I was saying,” Zhongli says, as if literally two hours had not passed, “we will need to decide on our history. As in how we met, how we fell in love, and so on. If your parents are as… enthusiastic as you describe them to be, then I imagine they will have lots of questions for us.”\r\n\r\nChilde winces. He can already imagine the plethora of questions his mother will ask them. \r\n\r\n“You’re right,” he says, taking a sip of his juice. He rolls the taste in his tongue while thinking through different scenarios. “Hmm… How we met…”\r\n\r\nZhongli waits patiently and watches as Childe taps his fingers on the wooden table. It has to be a story that’s both realistic and exciting enough to satisfy his parents and siblings...\r\n\r\nStruck by sudden genius, Childe sits up and grins at Zhongli. \r\n\r\n“How about this: I was assigned an important, top secret job here in Liyue. As I was getting acquainted with the place, we bumped into each other in the streets and you were kind enough to show me around. For the next several weeks, you would always accompany me everywhere and we became close friends. However, during my top secret mission, I was required to hunt down a powerful lord who sought to endanger the peace of the lands — and lo and behold, to my surprise , it was you. I was blindsided and betrayed! We battled for days and it was one of the greatest battles witnessed in Liyue history, but in the end, I emerged victorious and you surrendered.”\r\n\r\nHe leans back on his chair and raises his eyebrows at Zhongli. They stare at each other for the longest time. \r\n\r\n“Absolutely not,” Zhongli says.\r\n\r\nChilde frowns. “Okay, the battle was very close and you almost won.”\r\n\r\n“No.”\r\n\r\n“Fine, it was a draw.”\r\n\r\n“No.” Zhongli sighs. “How does that entail that we fell in love in any way?”\r\n\r\n“That comes after obviously. After you surrendered, we fell in love and cast aside our differences. You’re now retired and we’re madly in love with each other. The end.”\r\n\r\nZhongli pinches the bridge of his nose, shaking his head. “I doubt telling your parents that I once ‘sought to endanger the peace of the lands’ will serve as a good first impression for them.”\r\n\r\nHe… has a good point. “Alright, I’ll censor that out,” Childe mutters. He pauses, suddenly remembering another important factor. “If Teucer’s in the room, I’ll have to turn you into a rival toy company owner.”\r\n\r\nThe only thing the ex-Archon does is let out one last sigh of defeat before returning to his own meal. Since Zhongli no longer has anything to say to that, Childe considers he’s won this. Pleased, he falls back to what he usually finds himself doing, and that’s to watch Zhongli perform the most mundane of tasks. Only Zhongli can make drinking soup look like a graceful talent he’s honed for centuries.\r\n\r\nChilde stares down at his own bowl of noodles. He picks up as much as he can with his chopsticks and holds them out towards the ex-Archon. \r\n\r\n“Zhongli-xiansheng, let’s practice being a cute couple,” he says when Zhongli looks up. “Here, let me feed you.”\r\n\r\nHe catches a hint of amusement dancing in Zhongli’s eyes before he leans in, opening his mouth. \r\n\r\nChilde guides the chopsticks to Zhongli’s lips—or he would have if he was actually decent with these things. The noodles escape and slide down onto Zhongli’s lap, all over his custom-made tailored coat. Shit. Getting a stain on Zhongli’s immaculate clothes feels more of a crime than summoning an ancient God back from its slumber to destroy Liyue. \r\n\r\nFortunately, Zhongli chuckles and patiently cleans himself up. Afterwards, he scoops up some of his bamboo shoot soup and holds it out for Childe. \r\n\r\n“Drop the formalities. If we are lovers, we have no need for them,” he says. \r\n\r\nChilde nods, leaning in as Zhongli touches the tip of his spoon to his lips. He can barely focus on the taste when Zhongli’s amber eyes are fixed on him, watching his every move. \r\n\r\n“That’s true…” Childe mutters. “Call me Ajax.”\r\n\r\nZhongli offers another spoonful, tilting his head slightly. “Ajax?”\r\n\r\nChilde is slowly starting to regret suggesting they practice being a couple now. He wasn’t prepared to feel this flustered over Zhongli spoon feeding him soup of all things. \r\n\r\n“That’s my real name. My family are the only ones who still call me by that,” Childe explains once the soup has gone down his throat. He quickly sits back before Zhongli can offer more. “You can call me that when we’re with them.”\r\n\r\n“You do not like the name?” Zhongli asks, sipping a spoonful of his soup. Childe tries, and fails, to not think about how that same spoon has just touched his own lips ten seconds ago.\r\n\r\nHe pushes his noodles around his plate and forces his thoughts to stay on topic… Not that the topic is anything he’d like to be talking about. He’d been away from home so long that he had forgotten what the sound of his real name even sounded like. \r\n\r\n“It doesn’t really feel like it’s me any more,” he explains. \r\n\r\nAjax has long stopped being his real name and more a mask he puts on when he’s with his family. Ajax would have probably gotten married by now, living the domestic life his mother is so excited for him to experience. Ajax wouldn’t be a Harbinger, sugarcoating his adventures to his siblings and passing them off as fairy tales. \r\n\r\nChilde looks up towards the distance where the towering mountains pierce the clouds and wonders what direction will take him back to Snezhnaya. He can hardly remember what his room back home looks like. Even then, he knows, without a doubt, that his mother keeps it clean for him to return to, however long that will take. \r\n\r\n“Ajax would have stayed at home with his family, but I’m Childe now. Tartaglia,” he says. “I can’t go home until…”\r\n\r\nChilde’s voice trails away into silence. Until what? Until the Tsaritsa reaches her goal? He lets out a low laugh and shakes his head, shoving that train of thought away. Now’s not the best time to bring that up, especially with Zhongli of all people. \r\n\r\nWhen they finish their lunch, Childe automatically reaches for his bag of Mora while Zhongli gathers his purchases from earlier. The weather today is particularly humid; Childe can feel his clothes clinging onto him, making him yearn for the refreshing bite of Snezhnaya’s frozen breeze. And yet, Zhongli, who is dressed head to toe in several layers, doesn’t seem bothered at all. \r\n\r\nChilde doesn’t know what possesses him to lean in, enough that he catches a faint scent of the incense that was so overwhelming in the funeral parlour but pleasant when it’s on Zhongli. It’s only when Zhongli looks up that Childe realises he’s so close he can see his luminescent pupils dilate. The sounds of Wanmin Restaurant’s lunch time rush is nothing but a hush compared to the thoughts urging Childe to close the distance between them. \r\n\r\n“Practice,” Childe breathes out, because that’s the only explanation as to why he’s suddenly leaning in and brushing his lips against Zhongli’s cheek. He remains there for a few seconds, listening to the sound of his own pulse rampaging, allowing the smell of incense to fill his head. It takes everything in him to pull away. “Just practice.”\r\n\r\nNeither of them move. Childe is still close enough that he can see how thick Zhongli’s eyelashes are, how they cast shadows along the neat stroke of his eyeliner. Close enough that he sees Zhongli’s mouth parting, the tip of his tongue darting out to lick his bottom lip. \r\n\r\nHe wonders if that was enough practice. Maybe he should…\r\n\r\n“Are you two—?!” \r\n\r\nA startled gasp yanks Childe back to the present. He jerks back, spinning around to see Xiangling staring at both of them with eyes as wide as the sweltering sun. \r\n\r\n“Sorry, I couldn’t help but see...” She madly motions her arms between them, practically vibrating on the spot. “Oh, finally! I was beginning to wonder if it was ever going to happen!”\r\n\r\nWhat… was going to happen? Confused, Childe can only let out a nervous laugh, turning to Zhongli. \r\n\r\n“Yes, Xiangling,” Zhongli slowly says. “We are… happily together.”\r\n\r\nXiangling claps her hands as if this is the best news she’s heard in a long time. What makes it even more strange is that she calls over her father, who congratulates Childe by slamming a hand on his back so hard Childe is convinced that was a declaration for battle. \r\n\r\n“I’m happy for both of you! Xiangling and I knew it was only a matter of time before the two of you became a couple!” Chef Mao tells them. His loud voice booms throughout Chihu Rock, basically telling everyone the apparently good news. “Let me give you a discount to celebrate!”\r\n\r\nWell… if he’s getting a discount out of this, then Childe’s not complaining. The majority of Liyue may be convinced he murdered Rex Lapis, and seeing him with one of their most handsome bachelors is probably the last thing anyone wants—but hey, a discount is a discount. He happily pays for the meal and laughs it off when Xiangling jokes about inviting her to the wedding. \r\n\r\nSeriously, why is everyone obsessed with jumping straight into marriage here?\r\n\r\n“If Xiangling’s fallen for it, then I say we’re already pretty good at this fake lovers thing,” Childe says, grinning at Zhongli. \r\n\r\n“Hmm.” Zhongli doesn’t meet his gaze. He simply nods, and the two of them fall into silence as they walk back to the funeral parlour. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAfter Zhongli returned to the funeral parlour, Childe spent the rest of the day sorting through matters at the Northland Bank; just some loans that needed chasing here and there, a few people he had to threaten. Nothing out of the ordinary. \r\n\r\nIt’s quiet when he returns to his apartment. Had it not been for the sight of Teucer’s toys cluttering his hallway, he’d have probably forgotten his family are still here. Sighing, Childe picks each toy up, reminding himself to tell his little brother to take better care of them. Honestly, this kid… Childe sends him a crate full of new toys every month and he treats them like this? No wonder most of them are either lost or broken within a week!\r\n\r\nHe follows the toys to his lounge, pausing in his tracks as soon as he finds his parents resting on the couch. Childe’s face relaxes into a genuine smile. Both of them are asleep; his mother is curled up by his father’s side, who is quietly snoring while still holding the book he was likely in the middle of reading. \r\n\r\nAs quietly as he can, Childe sets down Teucer’s toys on the couch and reaches for the nearby blanket. He drapes it over his parents, holding his breath to make sure he makes no sound at all. \r\n\r\nEven so, the agility of the eleventh Harbinger is no match at all for his parents. His father peaks open one eye and lets out a big yawn.\r\n\r\n“Ajax,” he says, voice still thick with sleep. “Welcome back.”\r\n\r\nChilde offers him a sheepish smile and smooths the edges of the blanket over them, taking care not to wake his mother up. “I’m home. Sorry I woke you up. Is everyone already asleep?”\r\n\r\nHis father nods, rubbing his eyes. Under the dim light of the fireplace, Childe can see the harsh lines of age all over his face, coupled with scars he’d gotten from when he still used to hunt.\r\n\r\nWhen he was younger, Childe compared his father to the warriors in the bedtime stories he loved to hear before he went to bed. In a way, he’d gotten his habit of exaggerating stories from him, transforming reality into adventures, the mundane into legends. Now that he’s older, he knows the stories are just stories, and his father is just his father; no longer the warrior little Ajax saw him as. \r\n\r\nIt’s a bit unnerving, really; how age can change someone so drastically. \r\n\r\nOr, how he’s been away from home for so long that the difference is alarming him to this degree. \r\n\r\n“You should sleep soon too; you look tired,” his father says. “Don’t stay up too late.”\r\n\r\nChilde almost laughs at that. He’s in his early twenties and his father is still treating him like a kid—even funnier that, out of everyone in their family, it’s his father who knows just how bad Childe’s battlelust can get. He was the one who sent him to the Fatui, after all. \r\n\r\n“I won’t, I won’t,” Childe lies straight through his teeth. “You too, Father. Go back to sleep. We don’t want your headaches to return.”\r\n\r\nHe leaves his parents by the lounge and makes his way back to his chambers. As soon as he steps inside, he’s drained of what little energy he has left and wastes no time changing into his evening robes. There’s a few letters by his desk that he hasn’t opened yet, but none of them look urgent; Childe can leave those for another day. Unless they’re from his family or the Tsaritsa, then Childe rarely bothers to write back to anyone.\r\n\r\nHe’s just sinking into the warm confines of his blanket when he hears a faint noise by his doorway. Childe sits up and squints, barely making out three small figures hidden in the darkness. \r\n\r\n“Teucer? Anthon? Tonia…?” Childe rubs his eyes. Sure enough, the three of them emerge from the shadows one by one. “Why are you three still awake? You should be asleep!”\r\n\r\nTonia fiddles with the end of her braid; a habit Childe can see she still hasn’t abandoned. “Sorry, Brother… I… We were wondering if…” Her voice wanders off and she turns to her younger brothers. Teucer and Anthon nod encouragingly at her. “If you could tell us a story like you used to…”\r\n\r\nAll traces of drowsiness leave Childe within an instant. \r\n\r\n“You used to do it before…” Anthon mumbles, peeking out from behind Tonia. \r\n\r\nTonia quickly waves her hands. “But if you don’t want to do it anymore then—”\r\n\r\nChilde shakes his head. “Princess, don’t be silly. Of course I still want to do it.” He lifts the blanket and pats the space besides him. “Come here, you three. There’s plenty of room here.”\r\n\r\nThat’s a lie. Even the largest bed offered in Baiju Guesthouse is no match to fit three kids and a grown adult. Childe chuckles and hugs his siblings closer, making sure the blanket covers all of them. \r\n\r\n“Stay quiet though,” he reminds them, tucking a stray piece of Tonia’s hair behind her ear. “Mother and Father won’t be happy to find you all still awake.” \r\n\r\nThe three of them nod enthusiastically. Teucer raises a finger to his lips and Childe grins at him, ruffling his hair. \r\n\r\n“I still can’t believe all of you are here,” he muses. “Who’s looking after our house?”\r\n\r\n“Brother Taras and Sister Anya are there!” Teucer answers.\r\n\r\nSlowly, Childe nods. If he hasn’t seen his parents and younger siblings in a while, then he hasn’t seen Taras and Anya in forever. His older siblings had already moved out by the time Childe was enlisted into the Fatui.\r\n\r\n“Oh yeah, how are they doing?” he asks.\r\n\r\nTonia sits up and hugs one of Childe’s pillows to her chest. “Sister Anya is busy with her research, and Brother Taras recently broke up with his girlfriend.”\r\n\r\nChilde can’t help but laugh at that. “Wasn’t he with that one for several years?”\r\n\r\nShe giggles into her hand. “Yes… He’s not very happy about it. Both of them congratulate you about Mr. Zhongli though!”\r\n\r\nAnthon frowns. “No, Brother Taras said that he doesn’t believe you and that this is all bullshit.”\r\n\r\nTeucer gasps and points at Anthon. “You said a bad word!”\r\n\r\n“No bad words allowed, young man,” Childe says, lightly flicking Anthon on the tip of his nose. \r\n\r\n“Brother Taras said it first!”\r\n\r\n“Yes, well, our older brother is a bad man. We all know I’m the better brother here.”\r\n\r\nAnother lie, of course, because while their older brother is crass and hot-tempered, Childe doubts he’s ever killed anyone. \r\n\r\n“Anyway, enough about that.” Childe pulls his siblings closer and lowers his voice to a whisper. “Now, what story to tell you three… Did I ever tell you about the time I fought a basilisk…”\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nTeucer and Anthon are asleep before Childe can finish his story. Tonia is snuggled by his side, her eyelids gradually drooping close. Some of her curls have escaped her braid, tickling Childe’s collarbone. He smooths her hair down and lightly pats her head. \r\n\r\n“Tonia, go to sleep now,” Childe urges. \r\n\r\nShe yawns, moving closer to him. “I missed you, Brother.”\r\n\r\nHer voice is barely audible but he hears it enough. Childe twists one of her curls around his finger, sorting through emotions he hadn’t given himself a chance to feel in… ages. There’s no doubt he misses his family; he writes to them as often as he can to fill in the void of leaving home, but work keeps him busy enough to stop himself from brooding. Now that his family has crashed back into his life, he’s nowhere near prepared for all of this. \r\n\r\n“I missed you too,” Childe whispers.\r\n\r\n“I’m happy for you. I hope Mr. Zhongli makes you as happy as you make us, Brother.”\r\n\r\nChilde grits his teeth. All of a sudden, the warmth of his siblings curled around him feels like a giant weight. \r\n\r\n“Go to sleep, Princess,” Childe says. \r\n\r\nWhen he looks down, Tonia has already fallen asleep, but it doesn’t get rid of the bitter thought that Childe almost says out loud. \r\n\r\nSorry your big brother is nothing but a liar. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nIt’s even warmer the next day, which makes it all the more unbearable that his mother has been staring at this vegetable stall for almost an hour. Childe has resorted to using his hydro vision to cool himself down, but the humidity quickly reminds him that’s useless. Not for the first time in his life, he wishes he’d been gifted with a cryo vision rather than a hydro one. \r\n\r\nHow is his mother surviving? He’s been in Liyue for months and he’s close to melting. Meanwhile, his mother hasn’t even acknowledged the weather, and she’s casually walking around wearing one of her Snezhnayan dresses! Granted, she’s thankfully not wearing her furs anymore, but those dresses are still far too thick for this part of the world. \r\n\r\nHis mother taps him on the shoulder. \r\n\r\n“Ajax, dear, since it’s rather hot, do you think Mr. Zhongli would like okróshka? Or…” She trails off, her eyes travelling to the other side of the stall. “No, perhaps borscht would be better; he might not like cold soup... Oh no, I’m not sure they sell beetroot here… Ajax, what do you think?”\r\n\r\nChilde takes that as his cue to escape. He beams at his mother and places his hands on her shoulders, maneuvering her away from the stall. \r\n\r\n“How about I take care of the soup, and you can make us your famous pirog? I’ve missed it.”\r\n\r\nThey should have enough ingredients back in his apartment for that. No more shopping, please. \r\n\r\nHis mother beams at him and pats his cheek. “Anything for you, dear.”\r\n\r\nJust as Childe thinks they’re done for the day, she walks to the next stall and dashes all of his hopes. Sighing, he gives up and summons more water to splash himself with, running his fingers through his damp hair. \r\n\r\n“I was going to make syrniki for dessert, but that would cause problems if Anthon ate it…” his mother mumbles. \r\n\r\nChilde hears alarm bells ringing inside his head. “Please don’t give him any dairy products while he’s anywhere near my home.”\r\n\r\nHis mother laughs. “I can make tea cakes with cashew milk instead then.”\r\n\r\nCrisis averted, although it does mean they spend another hour in Liyue’s markets looking for more ingredients. Childe is convinced he’s hallucinating by the time he walks past Lumine, soaked from head to toe with lotus leaves stuck to her hair. Paimon waves as soon as she spots him.\r\n\r\n“Childe!” she calls out, flying to his side. \r\n\r\nAs expected, his mother’s attention is torn from the cart of flowers she’d been eyeing. Now, she’s staring at Paimon with a look that can only mean she’s trying not to gawk, but she is definitely gawking. In his mother’s defence, she’s a housewife with no vision; Childe doubts she’s ever seen a hilichurl up close, let alone whatever Paimon is supposed to be.\r\n\r\n“Mother, this is Lumine and Paimon,” Childe says, motioning towards both of them. “They’re my friends.”\r\n\r\nHis mother’s face relaxes into a friendly smile. “Oh, you must be the nice lady Teucer mentioned. It’s lovely to finally meet you. I’m Marisha.”\r\n\r\nShe reaches to shake Lumine’s hand, then stops when she realises Lumine is literally soaked to the bone. Water is still dripping from her clothes and her hair is stuck to her face that Childe can barely see her eyes. \r\n\r\nLumine waves at them with a blank expression. \r\n\r\n“Why do you look like you’ve just jumped down a waterfall?” Childe finally asks. \r\n\r\nLumine shrugs. “As a matter of fact, I did jump down a waterfall.”\r\n\r\nChilde exchanges glances with his mother, who has returned to gawking. \r\n\r\n“Food delivery,” Lumine says, as if that explains everything. “It’s nice to meet you as well, Mrs. Marisha.”\r\n\r\nPaimon swoops down and Childe’s mother lets out a laugh, shaking her small hand. Childe watches them with amusement. Sure, Paimon may look cute and harmless at first, but she’s the literal embodiment of evil. \r\n\r\nHis mother turns back to Lumine and motions towards the large basket of food they’ve gathered today. “We’re having dinner with Ajax’s fiance later—”\r\n\r\n“Mother, we’re not—”\r\n\r\n“—would you like to join us?”\r\n\r\nChilde swears he sees the corners of Lumine’s lips quirk up. On the other hand, Paimon is already snickering into her hands, kicking her legs about in the air. Childe imagines himself throwing her across the harbour to satisfy his growing urge for violence. \r\n\r\n“Um, I’m a bit busy tonight… Perhaps next time?” Lumine says.\r\n\r\nChilde’s mother nods. “That’s okay, dear. You’re always welcome any time. You too, Paimon.”\r\n\r\nThe only way Paimon will ever be invited for dinner at Childe’s house is if they end up serving her. Even then, Childe would rather avoid that, despite how many times Lumine has made the same joke about her being emergency food. \r\n\r\nLumine tucks her wet hair behind her ears and actually smirks at him. Childe is literally at a loss for words. “Enjoy yourselves, though. Ajax, tell Mr. Zhongli I said hello.”\r\n\r\nPaimon surges to his side and smacks him on the back. “And congratulations on the engagement!”\r\n\r\n“We’re not—”\r\n\r\nThe two of them dash off before he can finish his sentence. Childe massages his temples and takes two deep breaths. He never should have told Lumine and Paimon about Zhongli. They’re never going to let him live this down. \r\n\r\n“They seem nice,” his mother tells him. \r\n\r\nChilde has enough energy to fake a smile. Today is going to be a long day. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nWhen he hears a knock, Childe moves at record-breaking speed. He opens the door before Zhongli can knock a second time. \r\n\r\nHe’s prepared himself for this. They’ve cooked enough food to feed half of Liyue Harbour, and he’s gone through every romantic scenario in his head to please his parents. If all goes according to plan, then maybe tonight will be enough to convince his parents he’s found the love of his life and they can spend the rest of their two-week stay here simply being tourists. Is that too much to ask for?\r\n\r\nPrepared as he may be, Childe is not prepared to be greeted by a giant bouquet of flowers taller than his head. \r\n\r\n“For you,” Zhongli says, pushing the bouquet to him. One of the flowers almost pokes Childe in the eye. He dodges in the nick of time and peers at Zhongli through the stems. \r\n\r\n“Thanks…” Childe says, weighing the bouquet in his arms. How did Zhongli even pay for this? \r\n\r\n“The ferrylady suggested I bring this with me… I must admit I asked her for advice when meeting your family,” Zhongli explains, clearly aware of the direction of Childe\'s thoughts. \r\n\r\nHe looks at Childe in the eyes before ducking in and pressing his lips to his cheeks, essentially causing the Harbinger’s brain to implode. Childe’s now glad he’s carrying the world’s heaviest bouquet of flowers; it stops him from pressing his hand against the cheek Zhongli kissed like the lovestruck teenager he’s suddenly regressed into.\r\n\r\nBut enough about that—Zhongli asked the ferrylady for relationship advice? Childe would give anything to see that.\r\n\r\n“These are beautiful,” Childe say, hoping to Tsaritsa that he\'s actually got a vase in his apartment to put these flowers in. “You ready?”\r\n\r\nZhongli nods. Right on time, Childe’s mother pops her head into the corridor.\r\n\r\n“Ajax, I heard the door—oh!” She straightens as soon as she catches sight of Zhongli. \r\n\r\nZhongli steps forward, bowing. “You must be Ajax’s mother. I’m—”\r\n\r\n“Mr. Zhongli!” Childe’s mother rushes to them, all but pulling Zhongli into one of her bone-crushing hugs.\r\n\r\nChilde stands back, both amused and horrified. It’s only when he sees Zhongli struggling to decide whether he should hug her back or not that he decides he’s definitely more amused.\r\n\r\n“Oh Tsaritsa, Ajax never mentioned how handsome you are!\" his mother gushes. \"No wonder he talks nonstop about you in his letters!”\r\n\r\nNever mind. Now he’s just horrified. \r\n\r\n“Mother—”\r\n\r\n“Gavriil! Children!” Childe’s mother calls out. “Mr. Zhongli is here!”\r\n\r\nAll at once, four redheads pour into the corridor and crowd around Zhongli. Childe is pushed into the corner, but he’s more than happy to let Zhongli take this spotlight. \r\n\r\nHe’ll give him some credit though; from the outside, Zhongli is calm and polite, offering smiles to each and every one of his family members—but Childe’s been around the ex-Archon enough to notice the small changes in his body language. Zhongli’s shoulders are stiff. He’s way out of his comfort zone. Poor thing. \r\n\r\nChilde leans against the wall and pretends to be too busy admiring his gigantic bouquet. He’ll rescue his fake lover in a bit. \r\n\r\n“I’m Marisha, and this is my husband, Gavriil,” Childe’s mother says. She motions to the children, who are all dressed in their best clothes. “The youngest is Teucer, followed by Anthon, and then Tonia.”\r\n\r\nAt the mention of their names, Childe’s siblings flock around Zhongli, all speaking over each other. Childe only manages to hear Anthon ask Zhongli if he eats rocks for breakfast.\r\n\r\nLaughing, Childe swoops in to the rescue. He takes Zhongli by the hand and pulls him back to his side. “Let’s not crowd around him… Ahaha, it’s getting too claustrophobic in here.”\r\n\r\nTeucer tilts his head. “What does claws-straw-phoby mean?”\r\n\r\n“Claustrophobic, dummy,” Anthon huffs. “It means a fear of spaces that are too cramped and squishy!”\r\n\r\n“I’m not scared!” Teucer squints at Zhongli. “Is Mr. Zhongli scared?”\r\n\r\nChilde gently pushes his siblings out of the cramped hallway. “No, he’s not, but it’s better if we all sit down.”\r\n\r\n“It’s a pleasure to finally meet all of you. Ajax talks about his family all the time,” Zhongli says once all of them are sitting in the lounge.\r\n\r\nAs luck would have it, Childe did have a vase to put his flowers in. They look out of place in his bare apartment, but he likes them. \r\n\r\nHearing his real name, Childe averts his eyes from the flowers and fakes a smile towards his family. He’ll have to get used to Zhongli calling him Ajax. \r\n\r\n“Brother talks about you in his letters a lot too!” Anthon speaks up. “It’s always Zhongli this, Zhongli that—”\r\n\r\nChilde’s smile drops. “Anthon.”\r\n\r\nHis father lets out a low, hearty laugh. “We were all so shocked when we found out Ajax was getting married—”\r\n\r\n“Father, I told you that we’re not—”\r\n\r\n“Oh, but you’re considering marriage in the future, are you not?” Childe’s mother asks. Her eyes are so wide and full of hope that Childe can’t bring himself to deny her. “Mr. Zhongli, I hope you know what you’re getting into! Ajax is a lot of trouble.”\r\n\r\nZhongli turns to Childe. The softness in his eyes catches him off guard and he can only gawk as Zhongli smiles at him. \r\n\r\n“I’ve grown to like it,” Zhongli says, delivering another critical hit. \r\n\r\nChilde sits back, breathing deep. Zhongli is really good at this acting thing. He might even convince Childe at this point. \r\n\r\nThat should be a reassuring thing; the fact both of them are able to act so well it convinces everyone straight away. For some reason, though, Childe is unable to understand why it feels like there’s something… unpleasant clawing at his chest. \r\n\r\nIt… It doesn’t matter. Now’s not the best time to be brooding. \r\n\r\nHe averts his gaze away from Zhongli and claps his hands together, standing up. “Should we prepare dinner?”\r\n\r\nHis mother rises with him. “Yes! Mr. Zhongli, we’ve prepared a few Snezhnayan dishes; I hope that’s okay?”\r\n\r\n“I look forward to it.”\r\n\r\n“Brother also made his best soup!” Tonia adds. “Wait until you see it! It’s amazing!”\r\n\r\n“I’m sure it is.” Zhongli gives him that smile again. \r\n\r\nChilde is beginning to doubt he’ll ever survive this dinner. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nChilde is… confused, to say the least. They’ve just sat down for dinner, and all of the dishes are laid out as neatly as possible. There’s so much food that Childe is sure they will be well fed for the entire week, assuming it doesn’t go stale. His mother cooked Snezhnayan dishes for the main meal and for dessert, but Childe was in charge of the soup. He decided he would make something Zhongli should be familiar with, if only to give them some variety. \r\n\r\nSo, why in the Abyss is Zhongli staring at his calla lily seafood soup like he’s seconds away from lunging across the table and attacking it?\r\n\r\nAfter what seems like an entire minute of Zhongli staring at the soup enough to pierce a hole through it, Childe slowly scoops some into his bowl, offering him one of the largest tentacles. It falls into the soup with a quiet plop. Zhongli looks up at him with so much intensity that Childe almost takes the bowl away. \r\n\r\nThey give thanks to their meal and begin eating. From the corner of his eyes, Childe watches Zhongli raise his spoon to his lips. \r\n\r\n“...How’s the soup?” he asks under his breath. \r\n\r\n“Wonderful,” Zhongli says far, far too quickly that Childe knows he’s lying. \r\n\r\nNote to self: Never cook for Zhongli ever again. \r\n\r\n“Dear, here’s some pirog,” Childe’s mother says. She cuts a slice for Zhongli and slides it onto his plate. \r\n\r\n“Thank you. Is it a pie?”\r\n\r\n“Yes. It’s stuffed with cabbage and chicken.”\r\n\r\nZhongli pops a small piece into his mouth and closes his eyes. After a while, he nods. “It tastes lovely. The dough is so soft, it feels as though it is melting in my mouth.”\r\n\r\nChilde grins. “Ah, yes. Mother’s an expert at making pirog. You can\'t imagine how much I\'ve missed eating this.”\r\n\r\n“You boys flatter me too much…” His mother waves a hand to brush their compliments off, though Childe can tell she may as well be glowing from them. \r\n\r\n“So, Mr. Zhongli…” Shit. Childe knows that tone. He braces himself, waiting for the inevitable questions his mother was bound to unleash. “Ajax has told us so much about you, but I don’t believe he’s ever revealed how you two met…”\r\n\r\nHe takes a deep breath. He’s already thought of an answer to this—\r\n\r\n“We began as business partners,” Zhongli answers before he can get a word in.  “I had only thought of Ajax as a work colleague, but I admit his… eccentricities intrigued me and I sought to spend more time with him.”\r\n\r\nChilde blinks. That’s… not the story they agreed on. \r\n\r\n“At first, I wished to understand what made him different from everyone else, but as time passed, I found myself enjoying his company to the point where my days feel empty if he is not by my side.” Zhongli tilts his head towards him, resting his chin on his hands with a gentle smile. Childe can only stare back with wide eyes. He doesn’t even realise he’s dropped his spoon until he hears it clattering to the floor. “I am very much fond of him. He fills my days with a joy I have not felt in a long while.”\r\n\r\nWell… Fuck. Childe swallows the dry lump in his throat.\r\n\r\nZhongli is… really too good at this. \r\n\r\nAnthon fakes the sound of vomiting, quickly dispelling any sort of romantic atmosphere Zhongli has managed to create. Childe is unsure whether he’s grateful or not for this. \r\n\r\nOn the other hand, his mother looks like she’s about to cry any moment now. She reaches for a napkin and dabs the corner of her eyes, muttering something about ‘young love’. \r\n\r\nIf only she knew Zhongli is literally over six thousand years old. \r\n\r\n“Brother, you\'re almost as red as your hair!” Teucer cries out, pointing at Childe. \r\n\r\nTonia giggles. “He’s right!”\r\n\r\nOf course, pointing this out only makes things worse. Childe prays for the ground to swallow him whole, a bit like that time he fell straight through a crack in the forest and landed in the Abyss. Now would be a good time for that to happen again. \r\n\r\n“Ajax blushing… Now there\'s something I didn\'t think I\'d ever witness,” his father says, clearly impressed. Sure, because his father’s witnessed him almost murder twenty men when he was fourteen, but the sight of Childe blushing is what amazes him. \r\n\r\nAnthon joins in with Teucer pointing at Childe’s apparently red face. “He\'s in loooooove!”\r\n\r\nWhy did Childe think this was a good idea? This is only the first day. Does that mean he has to put up with thirteen more days of this? \r\n\r\n“Wow, all of you are really doing your best to embarrass me in front of Zhongli…” he mumbles, having lost nearly all of his will to live. He doesn’t even want to look at how Zhongli is reacting to this. If he’s lucky then maybe Zhongli will think he’s acting as well. \r\n\r\n“Oh, dear, you know we\'re only jesting,” his mother reassures him, ruffling his hair.  \r\n\r\nAs if choosing to have mercy on him, his parents change the topic by asking Zhongli more questions about himself. Thankfully, most of these are only basic questions about Zhongli’s job, his hobbies, how long he’s been in Liyue for… Zhongli answers all of them with no trouble at all, and it’s not long until Childe’s parents are charmed—as with anyone who comes into contact with the god. \r\n\r\nChilde allows their voices to fade into the background once Anthon starts asking Zhongli about what his favourite books are. He can’t help but think back to what Zhongli told his parents.\r\n\r\nIt shouldn’t be any surprise that Zhongli is so good at pretending to be his lover. After all, he did deceive Childe from the very beginning. For someone who comes across as graceful and polite, Childe forgets Zhongli can be as equally cunning and ruthless when he wants to be. \r\n\r\nChilde pushes his plate away and rises from the table. “I’m going to get dessert prepared. Excuse me.”\r\n\r\nHe doesn’t wait for them to respond, although he feels the unmistakable weight of Zhongli’s gaze following him. As soon as he’s in the kitchen, he lets out a deep sigh and almost hits himself for the stupid thoughts running through his head. \r\n\r\nNo, no, this is to be expected. He hates having to resort to deceit; he should have known he’d eventually feel like this. Besides, it was his idea to pretend to be Zhongli’s lover; Zhongli is only doing what their contract required him to do. \r\n\r\nHe’ll get used to this. He just needs… practice. Childe smirks, shaking his head to himself. How the tables turn…\r\n\r\nThe sound of footsteps pull Childe away from his musings. He’s not surprised to find Zhongli in the kitchen when he turns around. \r\n\r\n“Is everything okay?” Zhongli asks. \r\n\r\nChilde plasters a smile on his face. “I should be asking you that. They’re not too much, are they? My family can get very excitable.”\r\n\r\nZhongli runs his finger along the smooth surface of the counter. Even amidst the chaos Childe’s mother left in this kitchen, Zhongli manages to look regal, every bit the god he once was. \r\n\r\n“It’s nothing I cannot handle,” Zhongli says. “You have a lovely family.”\r\n\r\n“I know. I’ve missed them a lot.”\r\n\r\n“Do you not see them often?”\r\n\r\nChilde shakes his head and leans against the counter, folding his arms. “Not since I joined the Fatui. I regularly write to them though, especially Tonia.”\r\n\r\nZhongli remains where he’s standing at the other side of the kitchen. The distance between them may as well be miles away. Childe doesn’t like the way Zhongli looks at him as if he’s walking on eggshells. He forces out a half-hearted smirk. \r\n\r\n“Your story about how we met… That was some impressive acting,” Childe says. “Even I almost believed you for a second there.”\r\n\r\nZhongli looks down. “I’m glad it pleases you.”\r\n\r\nChilde isn’t sure how to respond to that. He settles for nodding, and quickly decides that wasn’t a good response at all because now they’ve fallen into silence that’s painfully awkward. He taps his foot against the tiles, wincing at how that only emphasises the lack of conversation between them. \r\n\r\n“Was my soup that bad?” he asks, desperate to break this tension. \r\n\r\nTo his surprise, there’s evident distress on Zhongli’s face. He offers Childe an apologetic smile. “Ah, yes. About that… I… I am not fond of seafood. I find the texture and the smell unpleasant, but once cut properly, I can appreciate it. Your soup itself was appetizing. Forgive me if my reaction offended you.”\r\n\r\nChilde manages to stop himself from laughing just in time. Zhongli, immovable and cold as rock, distressed by something so insignificant as seafood. It’s almost endearing. \r\n\r\n“You know, for a second there, I almost thought you were going to drop a meteor at the dinner table.\"\r\n\r\n“I considered it for a brief second, yes.”\r\n\r\nNow, Childe is unable to stop himself from laughing. “I think my parents adore you so much that they would have been impressed by that.”\r\n\r\nThey settle back into silence, but it’s no longer as unbearably awkward as it was earlier. Childe motions over his shoulder towards the food and drinks still on the counter. “We should get back. Would you mind carrying the drinks while I bring the dessert?”\r\n\r\n“Of course not.”\r\n\r\nZhongli walks across the kitchen. Childe is about to turn around to give him the drinks when he spots one of Teucer’s toys on the floor—\r\n\r\nAaand he doesn’t manage to warn Zhongli before he trips over it. Childe lurches forward, catching Zhongli in time. Or that was the plan. \r\n\r\nHe gulps, staring straight into the ex-Archon’s eyes. Somehow, they’ve ended up with Zhongli pinning him to the counter, and Childe, who had tried to grab Zhongli before he fell, manages to grab his ass instead. \r\n\r\n“Shit. Sorry, Teucer’s always leaving his toys all over the…” \r\n\r\nChilde shuts up as soon as his nose accidentally brushes against Zhongli’s. He’s so close he can literally feel his breath on his lips. \r\n\r\nFuck. \r\n\r\nShit. \r\n\r\nChilde loses any form of coherent thought. All he can do is stand there, gawking at Zhongli and trying his best not to pay attention to the fact his lips are dangerously close and it’ll only take one move for them to close that distance—\r\n\r\n“Brother, is the dessert ready yet—AH!” Tonia’s shrill scream pierces through the fog in Childe’s brain. He snaps out of it enough to see her covering her eyes, spinning around so fast she almost trips over her own feet. “I-I’m so sorry! I didn’t mean to interrupt!” \r\n\r\nShe runs off, most likely scarred for life. Childe should be horrified that his beloved sister has witnessed something like this, but all of the events from today are catching up to him. The only thing he can do is laugh into Zhongli’s neck. He lets out a weak chuckle and closes his eyes, breathing in the soothing scent of incense. \r\n\r\nFuck. He really can\'t think anymore.\r\n\r\nPossessed by Celestia knows what, Childe traces the tip of his nose along Zhongli’s neck. He waits for any sign of resistance, for Zhongli to push him away and tell him to stop, remind him there’s no one here and they don’t need to act, not right now. He doesn’t. Zhongli is as still as a statue, but Childe can see from the corner of his eyes that he grips the counter tighter. \r\n\r\nHe should stop. He should pull away and laugh it off. They don’t need to be doing this now.\r\n\r\nPractice, he reminds himself as his lips move on their own accord, pressing against the smooth column of Zhongli’s neck. He hears the ex-Archon breathe in. Childe stills, waiting for that sign to force him to finally stop. \r\n\r\nZhongli’s hand pushes against the back of his head, keeping him in place.\r\n\r\nIt’s nothing, Childe repeats again and again, until it’s the only thought that runs through his head and keeps him grounded. Nothing, nothing. Nothing. He slides his lips along Zhongli’s neck, pressing closer when he feels fingers carding through his hair. Nothing. He sucks just under Zhongli’s jaw and listens to the sharp hiss that follows soon after. Nothing. Zhongli tilts his head; a silent invitation for more when they should be stopping, they shouldn’t be doing this. It’s nothing. Childe kisses up the edge of his jaw, his chin, the corner of his lips, and—\r\n\r\n“Ajax? Is everything okay?”\r\n\r\nChilde jolts back. At the same time, Zhongli throws himself off him so fast that he’s at the other side of the kitchen within the blink of an eye. \r\n\r\n“Dear, is the dessert not ready yet?” Childe’s mother asks, peering into the kitchen door. She looks between him and Zhongli, raising her eyebrows. \r\n\r\nChilde quickly turns to the counter, reaching for the dessert they’ve clearly forgotten. Next to him, Zhongli gathers the drinks, and Childe makes the mistake of looking at him. His eyes immediately land on the red mark that’s slowly blooming on the ex-Archon\'s neck. \r\n\r\nGreat. Fucking great. He’s gone and given Zhongli a motherfucking hickey right in the middle of dinner. As if it wasn’t already obvious what they’ve been doing here. \r\n\r\n“Everything’s fine,” Childe tells his mother, who clearly does not believe anything that’s coming out of his mouth. “Everything’s just fine.”', 'set_in_stone.jpg', '2021-04-25 21:45:52.801524', '2021-04-26 10:15:23.514063', '0', '1', 'set_in_stone_02', '1', '2', 'Set in Stone');
INSERT INTO `sueed_article` VALUES ('3', 'Set in Stone 03', 'the same with 01', 'Chapter 3: A Losing Battle\r\n\r\n“So, you kissed Zhongli and now you’re having a mental crisis because you actually enjoyed it.”\r\n\r\nChilde almost loses focus after what Lumine said. He ducks down in time, hearing the hiss of a blade narrowly miss his cheek, and kicks the treasure hoarder right in the chest. It takes them a second to regain their balance, but one second is all it takes for him to drive his blade into their gut.\r\n\r\n“I didn’t kiss him,” Childe says, shooting her a quick glare as the treasure hoarder flails in his arms. He twists the blade deeper, aiming under their ribs, and smirks when they finally go limp. \r\n\r\nThere’s no time for a smug victory though. Just as he drops the body and summons his hydro blades away, another treasure hoarder is charging towards him with a shovel of all things. He jumps back and aims with his bow, firing an arrow straight into their… shoulder. Drat. He meant to aim for their neck, but that’s close enough. He fires another shot and, thankfully, that hits home. The large man collapses into the snow.\r\n\r\n“You were slurping up his neck! You gave him a hickey!” he hears Paimon yelling.\r\n\r\n“And you grabbed his ass,” Lumine adds.\r\n\r\nBefore Childe can defend himself against those ghastly accusations, the rest of the treasure hoarders decide it’s a good idea to rush towards him. He happily brandishes his blades again and meets them halfway. The more time passes, the harsher the bite of the snowstorm. He grits his teeth through the cold and lets adrenaline keep him warm. \r\n\r\nIt doesn’t take long to get rid of the remaining hoarders. Half of them panic and scamper away, tripping in the snow like babies who had just learnt how to walk. If Childe wasn’t close to freezing his balls off, he’d have chased after them to finish the job. \r\n\r\nSighing, he calls his blades away and squats down, sifting through the corpses’ belongings. The sight of blood seeping into snow is a sight he has not seen in far, far too long.\r\n\r\nThere was always something so beautiful about the sight of vibrant crimson tarnishing the pure white valleys of his homeland. Come the next morning, a new blanket of snow would cover everything from the previous day. No matter how ghastly the scene, how thick the blood had soaked its surroundings, Snezhnayan snowstorms are always harsher. It is, after all, the last and most dangerous enemy you will ever face in the harsh lands of Snezhnaya. \r\n\r\nHe’s always found comfort in it. Regardless of how far his family was, he knew they would be back home surrounded by that unchanging snow. He’d chosen the chaotic life of the Harbingers rather than remain at home with them, but he liked to cling onto useless sentiments such as this.\r\n\r\nA sudden gust of freezing wind pulls Childe away from his thoughts. He braces himself and returns to the task at hand. He’s been hanging around Zhongli too much; the ex-Archon’s penchant for nostalgia is rubbing off on him. \r\n\r\nHe returns to searching the corpses, although it’s not long until he sees there’s not much to find. For a group that calls themselves treasure hoarders, Childe barely sees any treasure at all; just a handful of Mora and some insignias. \r\n\r\nLumine crouches down, warming her hands by the campfire the treasure hoarders kindly left behind. “Anyway, it doesn’t matter what you did. The fact is that you enjoyed it.”\r\n\r\nChilde sits opposite her, throwing all of the Mora and insignias in Paimon’s direction. The flames of the campfire dance between them as Lumine stares at him, waiting for him to deny it. He almost does, but then she raises an eyebrow and all he can do is look away and grumble to himself.\r\n\r\n“It’s just a natural reaction. This whole fake lovers agreement is messing with my head.”\r\n\r\n“What do you mean by that exactly?”\r\n\r\nHe shrugs, drawing circles along the snow with his finger. Snow seeps into his gloves and it almost feels like he’s back home. He gathers a handful and crushes it into his palm, allowing the ice to numb his skin while he struggles to think of an answer.\r\n\r\n“Zhongli is… really good at acting. It’s easy to get lost in it.”\r\n\r\nLast night, he thought about it in bed far longer than he should have. The memory was so vivid that he could still taste Zhongli’s skin and hear the sharp breaths he took when Childe slid his lips along his neck. Childe wondered, for a brief second, what other noises Zhongli would have made if he’d bit down, hard. Curiosity tugged at the corner of his brain; it yearned to know the ranges of Zhongli’s expressions, his reactions, anything outside of his normal, stoic shell. \r\n\r\nAnd then Childe stopped there, literally slapping himself out of it before he could go too far. One day into this stupid contract and he was already making this more difficult than it had to be. \r\n\r\nChilde glances up and catches Lumine and Paimon looking at each other. Their expressions make it look like they know something he doesn’t. \r\n\r\n“I think what you need to ask yourself is if you would have reacted like this if you were faking a relationship with someone else instead,” Lumine says after a while.\r\n\r\nChilde can only frown at that. \r\n\r\nPaimon bobs in the air, waving a finger. “As in, would you be falling for the act if you faked a relationship with Venti instead?”\r\n\r\nShe points at the bard Childe has completely forgotten about. The bard strums his lyre from the fence he’s been sitting on all this time. He didn’t even help them fight the treasure hoarders. All he’s been doing is provide background music. \r\n\r\n“We literally just met today,” Childe says. \r\n\r\nAccording to Paimon’s babble, Venti was the Anemo Archon whose gnosis was stolen by La Signora. For some reason, he didn’t even so much as bat an eyelid when he found out Childe was another Harbinger. A shame, because Childe wouldn’t have minded a fight, although this guy doesn’t look like he’ll be much of a challenge. \r\n\r\nWhen La Signora mentioned stealing the Anemo Archon’s gnosis, Childe didn’t expect it would come from a bard who spoke with rhymes every five seconds. \r\n\r\n“You’re giving Morax too much credit,” Venti says, his voice sounding like a song. “That buffoon wouldn’t be able to act even if you offered him a million Mora.”\r\n\r\n“How did Zhongli even react when you slurped up his neck?” Paimon asks. \r\n\r\n“Can you please stop saying it like that?” Childe scowls at her. “He didn’t… do anything. He just stayed there.”\r\n\r\nPaimon shrugs. “Maybe he liked it.”\r\n\r\nChilde groans. He is not about to have this conversation with Paimon of all people.\r\n\r\n“Like I said, it’s a normal reaction. I dived into this fake relationship thing without thinking about it, so I just… got carried away. It won’t happen again. Not unless we need to fake a few kisses in front of my family but they won’t be anything like… like that. ”\r\n\r\nIt’s what makes the most sense in his head. Zhongli is a very attractive man, and he’s also one of the few people Childe can consider a friend. Of course his body is going to have some sort of positive reaction to him… Besides, it’s completely natural for a man of his age to react like that. He’s young, he’s got raging hormones! It’s normal!\r\n\r\nLumine clears her throat. “You still didn’t answer my question.”\r\n\r\n“What question?”\r\n\r\n“Would you have reacted like this if you faked a relationship with someone else instead?”\r\n\r\n“Yes…?” Childe trails off with a frown. Well… no, if he did this with Lumine instead, he doesn’t think it would have been the same. She’s practically a sister to him. “I don’t know—I mean, yes. Yeah?”\r\n\r\nLumine and Paimon don’t look convinced. To be honest, Childe doesn’t think he’s convinced himself either—but it’s not like he knows anyone else he can fake a relationship with. Aside from Zhongli and Lumine, he’s only ever around the other Harbingers, and there’s no way that could be an option. He can’t even stand being in the same room as the rest of the Harbingers, let alone spending two weeks pretending to be in love with any of them. \r\n\r\nVenti joins them, setting aside his lyre to warm his hands by the campfire. “How’s Morax doing these days? Or, well, I guess he’s calling himself Zhongli now.”\r\n\r\nChilde is grateful for the change of topic. “He works as a consultant in Wangsheng Funeral Parlour now. Don’t really know why he’s still working when I’m the one who ends up paying for him all the time.”\r\n\r\nLumine shuffles closer to the fire and shivers when a gust of wind barrels through them. Childe doesn’t understand why she insisted on exploring this barren mountain of ice, and moreover, why she decided to explore without wearing adequate clothes. He certainly hopes she doesn’t intend on going to Snezhnaya in that sleeveless dress of hers. \r\n\r\n“Venti, you and Zhongli knew each other when you were Archons, didn’t you? He mentioned he had a friend who always gave him dandelion wine,” Lumine says once she’s stopped shivering. \r\n\r\n“He called me a friend? That’s a surprise.”\r\n\r\nPaimon nods. “He also called you a disgrace to the arts.”\r\n\r\nAt this, the bard throws his head back and laughs. “Yeah, we knew each other before but he was no fun. He never smiled, not even when he was around that woman.”\r\n\r\n“Woman?” Paimon scratches her head. “What woman?”\r\n\r\n“The Goddess of Dust. Guizhong.”\r\n\r\nChilde squints at the fire, vaguely recognising the name. All he knows is that she was a Goddess who worked alongside Zhongli—or Morax, as he had once been called—but ultimately died during the Archon War. \r\n\r\nHe’s never given it much thought. Sometimes, it’s all too easy to forget Zhongli was a god. When he’s with Zhongli, he doesn’t think of him as the ex-Archon who ruled over Liyue for thousands of years. Even when he was searching for the gnosis, it never occurred to him that Zhongli could be anything more than a man who simply knew too much about Liyue. \r\n\r\n“Oh, Paimon’s heard about the Goddess of Dust! Lumine met this researcher who knew all about her! She said she was Rex Lapis’ ally and best friend, and that she complimented his brawns with her brains. Wasn’t the Guili Plains named after them?”\r\n\r\nVenti strums his lyre. “That’s right. They were always together, even until she died.”\r\n\r\nChilde pokes a stick into the campfire, watching the flames until they morph into a blur of amber, scarlet, and gold. They were always together, even until she died. It’s the worst time for the little voice in his head to pop up, wondering if, maybe, the reason why he doesn’t think about Zhongli being an ex-Archon is because it reminds him of the differences between them. Childe’s own lifespan may as well be minuscule seconds compared to the countless centuries Zhongli has lived through. It\'s nothing. It’s a blink of an eye against an eternity.\r\n\r\nHe grinds his teeth together, throwing the branch into the flames. Vaguely, he hears Venti singing a song as the howling winds of Dragonspine join in. He can’t bring himself to appreciate it. \r\n\r\nChilde inhales, exhales, watching his breath puff out into the unforgiving breeze. He really is getting far too sentimental for his own good.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAfter Lumine almost freezes to death in Dragonspine, Childe manages to convince her to call it quits for the day. He also urges her to wear appropriate clothes next time; running around trying to find the nearest torch or campfire every five minutes gets boring very, very quickly. \r\n\r\nChilde is craving for a nice, warm bath when he returns to Liyue, but, as luck would have it, his parents have other plans. \r\n\r\n“We’re going on a date,” his mother announces, motioning towards the fancy dress she’s wearing. Childe thinks it looks the same as her other dresses, though he doesn’t dare say that out loud. \r\n\r\n“A date? Who?”\r\n\r\n“Your father and I, of course!” his mother says. She pushes him out of the lounge and towards the front door, even though Childe’s only been home for ten seconds. “Mr. Zhongli suggested that we should watch this play at the Heyu Tea House, and your father decided it would be a perfect opportunity for the two of us to have a date. Isn’t that romantic?”\r\n\r\nChilde trips into the hallway. “Uh. Yes…? But why are you pushing me out of the door?”\r\n\r\nTypical. His family has only been here for two days and he’s already being thrown out of his own apartment.\r\n\r\n“Look after the children while we’re gone, Ajax,” his father tells him. “Mr. Zhongli is already with them. I heard he was taking them out of the harbour.”\r\n\r\nChilde blinks. Why is he only hearing about this now? Since when did his family make plans with Zhongli instead of him?\r\n\r\n“What? Where? Huh?”\r\n\r\nLaughing, his mother pats him on the head and literally shoves him out of the apartment. “They only left a few minutes ago. You should be able to catch them before they leave the harbour.”\r\n\r\nWith that, she blows him a kiss and closes the door in his face. \r\n\r\nChilde stands there, shocked beyond belief because Zhongli has somehow convinced his parents to go on a date and he’s now out babysitting Tonia, Teucer, and Anthon. \r\n\r\nHe’s let Lumine take care of Teucer before, so the thought of Zhongli with his siblings shouldn’t invoke fear into his bones. And then he thinks about Teucer playing hide and seek with Zhongli, only to cheat during the game and, in turn, the ex-Archon recognises that as breaking one of his contracts. \r\n\r\nArchons above. Childe sprints off in the direction of the harbour, half convinced Zhongli has already dropped a meteor on his siblings.\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nOkay, he was overreacting. When Childe finds them, they’re in the fields outside Liyue and no one has yet been flattened by any falling meteors. Anthon is climbing what looks one of Zhongli’s geo pillars and Tonia is staring up at him as if she’s contemplating whether she wants to join in or tell him to come down. Teucer is the first to spot Childe, his face breaking out into a giant grin. \r\n\r\n“Brother! You’re here! Look what Mr. Zhongli can do!” \r\n\r\nChilde looks. The moment his eyes land on Zhongli, he remembers the last time he saw him, he was—as Paimon crudely puts it—slurping up his neck. \r\n\r\nDon’t think about it, please, Childe begs himself as his eyes trail down Zhongli’s face, landing on the spot under his jaw. \r\n\r\nFuck. The hickey is still there. And it’s gotten worse. \r\n\r\n“Hello, Ajax,” Zhongli greets, smiling. \r\n\r\nChilde wants to shake him by the shoulders. Is Zhongli completely unaware that he’s got Teyvat’s largest hickey on his neck? Why didn’t he cover that up? Does he even care?\r\n\r\n“Hi,” Childe all but squeaks out. \r\n\r\nIf Zhongli has spoken to his parents today then there’s no doubt they’ve seen that gigantic hickey. Fuck, half of Liyue Harbour must have already seen it if Zhongli’s walking around without a care in the world. \r\n\r\nChilde can already imagine the bulletin board in Feiyun Slope being updated this very second: ‘Mr. Zhongli, the graceful and knowledgeable consultant of Wangsheng Funeral Parlour, spotted walking around with a large hickey on his neck. Who could his secret lover be?’\r\n\r\nOh, who is Childe kidding? Of course they’re going to think it’s him. Xiangling and her father practically announced it to the whole harbour yesterday. \r\n\r\nGreat. Now the harbour thinks he’s killed Rex Lapis and he’s tried sucking the blood out of Zhongli’s neck. \r\n\r\nEh, whatever. Childe’s never cared about what people thought of him. If everyone in Liyue Harbour thinks he’s suddenly ravishing Zhongli then they can carry on with that. He can think of worse rumours.\r\n\r\n“You… aren’t going to cover that up?” Childe asks, keeping his eyes fixed on his siblings in a desperate attempt to ignore Zhongli’s neck. Tonia has decided to join Anthon in climbing the geo pillars while Teucer cheers them on.\r\n\r\nFrom the corner of his eyes, Childe sees Zhongli tilt his head at him. \r\n\r\n“Your neck,” Childe elaborates. “Surely you must have seen what I, uh, did to you last night.”\r\n\r\nHe winces. He should have worded that better. \r\n\r\n“Oh, this? Master Hu Tao found great amusement in it this morning. She says she applauds you. I fail to understand why something like this is worthy of praise.”\r\n\r\nNow, Childe turns to him, unable to hide the look of horror slowly dawning on his face. \r\n\r\nZhongli blinks, lifting a hand to rub his neck. “It is merely a bruise from when you were—”\r\n\r\n“Okay. That’s… great to know,” Childe speaks over him, faking a laugh that must have sounded more like a sob. \r\n\r\nIs Zhongli really this dense? Is he playing around with Childe? Surely he can’t have been the first person to ever plant a hickey on this guy? \r\n\r\nThen again, considering that Zhongli was a literal god, Childe doubts he was an easy catch—but who could be sure? Zhongli has lived for thousands of years, he must have been with someone before. Maybe Guizhong, or another god, or maybe even some lucky mortal. \r\n\r\nChilde shakes his head to himself. He’s going to stop thinking about this. Debating over Zhongli’s sex life was not part of their contract. \r\n\r\n“Brother, look! I’m so high up! Mr. Zhongli is so cool!” \r\n\r\nBless Anthon for coming in at the right time to distract him. Childe plasters on the largest smile and waves at his younger brother. From atop the geo pillar, Anthon waves back, his glasses almost falling off his face in all his excitement. \r\n\r\n“Even cooler than me?” Childe asks. “You’re going to make me jealous.”\r\n\r\n“A-Ah… This is higher than I expected…” he hears Tonia say once she’s clambered up the other pillar. Her hair has escaped out of its bun; it’s a wonder she can see anything with it flying all over the place.\r\n\r\nTonia pushes her hair away from her eyes. Within seconds, her complexion grow paler as soon as she sees how high up she is. \r\n\r\nHe takes a step closer, holding out his arms. “You alright, Princess? Want me to help you come down?”\r\n\r\nTonia pouts and shakes her head, reminding Childe that stubbornness runs in their family. \r\n\r\n“Sister Tonia! Hurry up and catch it! The glowy thing!” Teucer jumps up and down, pointing at what Childe assumes is the ‘glowy thing’, which is, in fact, a geo crystalfly. “It’s going to fly away!”\r\n\r\nTonia huffs and leans over the edge of the pillar. “I’m trying! AH—”\r\n\r\nChilde’s heart stops when she falls off. He hasn’t even managed to blink before Zhongli is already there, catching Tonia into his arms. \r\n\r\n“Careful,” Zhongli says, helping her back to her feet. Even from where Childe is standing, he can see that Tonia’s face has turned as red as her hair. \r\n\r\nShe stumbles away from Zhongli. “I-I’m sorry!”\r\n\r\nChilde wastes no time sprinting to them. “Are you hurt?” \r\n\r\n“No, I’m fine... I caught this.” \r\n\r\nTonia lifts her palms and shows him a glowing orb nestled in her grasp.  It pulses a golden glow that dwindles weaker and weaker by the second until it completely dies out. In its place is what looks like a lacklustre diamond.\r\n\r\nAnthon jumps down the pillar and barges between Childe and Tonia, waving a diamond of his own. “I have one too! What is it?”\r\n\r\n“A crystalfly, specifically a geo crystalfly. They are beings of pure elemental energy absorbed from the atmosphere,” Zhongli answers them and motions towards the diamond Tonia is holding. “That is their core. The lifespan of a crystalfly is fleeting; once it senses it is in danger, it will dissipate into the air. If caught, their crystal cores are often used as ingredients for alchemy.”\r\n\r\nTo Childe’s great amusement, his siblings all go oooooh in simultaneous chorus. It’s one of Zhongli’s many talents; sharing useless trivia and making it sound interesting for any audience, regardless of their age. \r\n\r\nTeucer pops his head into their little group huddle, squinting at Zhongli. “Mr. Zhongli, can you fight too?”\r\n\r\nAnthon’s eyes light up. “Are you as strong as Big Brother?”\r\n\r\n“No one is as strong as Big Brother!”\r\n\r\nChilde laughs. That’s a good question, actually, and it’s a reminder that Childe has not yet fought Zhongli at all, which he considers a crime considering he has always wanted to test how strong the oldest Archon of Teyvat could be. \r\n\r\nIt won’t be the same now that Zhongli no longer has his gnosis though. Shame. \r\n\r\nGrinning, he turns to the man in question. The expression on Zhongli’s face looks like he already knows what Childe is going to ask him. \r\n\r\n“How about we find out, Zhongli?” Childe asks. “Let’s have spar to entertain the kids?”\r\n\r\nAs expected, the only response Childe receives is a minuscule frown. Zhongli’s amber eyes flicker between him and his siblings, as if weighing the consequences between battling Childe or risking the disappointment of the children should he refuse. \r\n\r\n“Just a quick spar,” Childe promises. “Indulge me a little.”\r\n\r\nTonia claps her hands while Anthon and Teucer jump up and down, inching closer and closer to Zhongli. Funnily enough, Childe notices Zhongli’s shoulders have tensed up. \r\n\r\n“Yes!” the children cheer. \r\n\r\nWithin seconds, Zhongli’s shoulders deflate and he lets out a huff of defeat. \r\n\r\n“A quick spar,” he sternly repeats.\r\n\r\nPleased, Childe tells his siblings to stand back. All three of them scurry behind a fence.\r\n\r\nHe almost wants to laugh at the notion of a quick spar. Quick spar or not, Childe can already feel the familiar bubble of adrenaline that feeds him every day. It’s a flicker of flames touching a valley of grass; he finds it hard to control, and most times he does not. He relishes in the moment when he can strike and let everything go, be the weapon he has trained to be. \r\n\r\nEvery battle, he thinks, is the same; whether it\'s a spar, or a training session, or a duel that almost kills him. It\'s only in these moments that Childe truly feels alive. \r\n\r\nZhongli stands tall at the other side of the field, the tails of his coat rippling in the wind. Today, Liyue has been covered in a swarm of dark, grey clouds, a stark contrast to the blinding heat from this past week. Childe senses a storm is approaching soon. He summons his bow and weighs it in his hands, keeping his gaze fixed on Zhongli.\r\n\r\nEven from this distance, Zhongli\'s eyes are piercing and bright. With a wave of an arm, his spear materialises by his side.\r\n\r\n“Are you ready?” he asks. \r\n\r\nChilde pulls back the bowstring and shoots. Zhongli only has to tilt his head slightly for the arrow to hurtle past his ear. \r\n\r\nChilde grins. “Oh yeah.” \r\n\r\nZhongli lunges forward; a blur of gold and onyx accompanied by the whistle of the wind and the rain of his spears. In the blink of an eye, the ex-Archon is in front of him and Childe parries his attack with his blades. His grin widens and he pushes forward, eyes transfixed on Zhongli and nothing but Zhongli. The ground trembles beneath his feet as Zhongli refuses to budge. Childe’s always known he was strong and the thought of finally, finally witnessing it this second sends euphoria through his veins. \r\n\r\nIn unison, the two of them jump back. Childe is the first to strike again. The drumming of his pulse rises in his ears until it’s all he hears. Childe moves with it, a deafening chorus that only grows louder every time his blades clash with Zhongli’s spear. They match each other like music and choreography; a strike and another parry, a feint to the side and a dodge.\r\n\r\nIt’s impossible to fathom how long this goes for; five seconds, an hour, a lifetime, but the longer it lasts, the more he notices that Zhongli is on the defensive. His expression remains as immovable as stone. He’s calm. He’s holding back. \r\n\r\nHe grits his teeth. No. He wants more. \r\n\r\nChilde retreats, catching the slight hesitation flashing in Zhongli’s face. He slots his blades together, transforming it into a polearm. \r\n\r\n“You’re holding back,” Childe says, twisting the weapon in his hand. It weighs as any polearm would; solidified water rushing forward like a tide in a storm. With this moment of reprieve, Childe feels the tapping of raindrops on his face. Above them, the grey clouds are stirring, groaning, and thunder grumbles in the distance. \r\n\r\nZhongli doesn’t say anything—Childe doesn’t give him a chance to. He launches into the air and plunges down where the ex-Archon is standing. Water erupts around them as Zhongli blocks his attack, still as calm and graceful as ever. Then, a crackle of electricity dances along the droplets in the air, not enough to be seen, but enough to feel it as a prickle on your skin or a caress along your cheek. It’s the only warning Zhongli gets before lightning bursts between them. \r\n\r\nChilde jumps back, reigning his delusion in. Electricity continues to bristle in his veins like a thousand, shuddering needles, and there’s a faint scent of burning skin mixed with the rain-wet earth. He flexes his hands until the pain ebbs away and the rain howls louder. \r\n\r\nHe’d timed it perfectly so his siblings would think that lightning came from the storm, but he knows Zhongli is not so easily fooled. Zhongli rises from where he’d thrown himself back. He stands tall once again, but long gone is the firm serenity that refused to leave his face. His eyes narrow at Childe, jaws clenched. The tails of his coat are singed, his shirt soaked and clinging to him like a second skin, the golden tips of his hair glowing against the dark sky. \r\n\r\nFor a second, the sight leaves Childe breathless. \r\n\r\nThe sound of the storm amplifies in his head. All he hears is thunder drumming in his pulse, louder, louder. Beneath him, the ground groans, shakes, and it takes him a second too long to realise this is not because of the storm. Pillars erupt from where he’s standing, throwing him back. He lands in a river and vaguely registers the ache spreading down his spine. \r\n\r\nIn the corner of his eyes, he notices that the ex-Archon is nowhere to be seen—\r\n\r\nHe dives back as Zhongli descends on him. There’s a burst of water and debris, of lightning and rain. River water soaks into his clothes and Zhongli is on top of him, thighs pressed on either side of Childe’s waist, and his spear lodged into the ground next to his head. Strands of Zhongli’s hair tickle Childe’s cheeks; he’s so close Childe can see the rouge drawn under his eyes is now smudged from the rain. So close he can feel the warmth of his body pressed against him. \r\n\r\nChilde hisses a breath in. His hands move without him thinking about it. He grips Zhongli\'s thighs. Then, he thrusts his hips up—and there’s a maddening second where it feels good, too good, and he sees Zhongli’s eyes widen, hears him gasp, and Childe almost does it again, again—\r\n\r\nZhongli pushes himself off him, ripping his spear off the ground. \r\n\r\n“That\'s enough,” he grits out. \r\n\r\nThe stern edge in his voice snaps Childe out of it like a bucket of cold water. He blinks back into reality and struggles to catch up with the rampaging of his thoughts. Zhongli turns his back on him and summons his spear away.\r\n\r\nShit, Childe thinks. Shit. That wasn’t supposed to happen. That shouldn’t have happened—\r\n\r\n“That was so cool!”\r\n\r\nTeucer jumps into view with the largest grin Childe has ever seen on him. And really, nothing yanks you away from your raging hormone-induced thoughts more than a younger sibling staring at you like you’re the world’s greatest hero. \r\n\r\nChilde finally has enough strength to stand back up, but the world spins faster than a rolling geovishap and Childe thinks he might be sick. Or that might be all these strange emotions threatening to bubble out of his throat. He rubs his head, trying his best to ignore them. \r\n\r\n“Who won?” Anthon asks, shaking Childe’s elbow. “Did you win, Brother?”\r\n\r\nChilde swallows the dry lump in his throat. “It was a draw.”\r\n\r\nWhen he looks at Zhongli again, he doesn’t know whether to be relieved or worried that the ex-Archon still has his back turned to them. \r\n\r\nTeucer wails. “Aaw, that’s no fun!”\r\n\r\n“You know what else isn’t fun?” Childe ruffles Teucer’s hair and tickles his sides, chuckling when his brother screams louder than the storm itself. “Thunderstorms. Come on, it’s pouring it down now. Let’s get back home before we all get sick.”\r\n\r\nChilde needs a bath, he decides as his brain fills his thoughts with images of Zhongli gasping above him. A very, very cold bath. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nNow that he’s finished freezing all of the inappropriate thoughts out of his system, Childe leaves the bathroom and yawns into his hand. He’s surprised to find that his apartment is eerily silent. It’s late in the evening but his siblings are usually far too stubborn to sleep this early. \r\n\r\nHe peeks into their room and finds a miracle. \r\n\r\n“Wow, you got them to fall asleep.” Childe whistles, leaning on the doorframe. “That takes talent, xiansheng.”\r\n\r\nZhongli sits on the edge of the bed, smoothing down the blanket over the slumbering forms of Childe’s siblings. It really is a miracle; Tonia, Teucer, and Anthon are all huddled together and snoring in unison. Childe’s bath didn’t even last that long; probably over half an hour. Usually, it takes him at least an hour of stories for his siblings to finally fall asleep.\r\n\r\nUpon hearing his voice, Zhongli looks up. “They asked me to tell them a story.”\r\n\r\nChilde chuckles, thinking back to all of Zhongli’s stories. His voice is always calm and soothing; it’s no wonder the kids fell asleep so quickly.\r\n\r\n“Did you tell them about the amazing Rex Lapis?”\r\n\r\nZhongli’s eyes crinkle with amusement. “Those are the stories I know best.”\r\n\r\n“You should tell me some of them one day,” Childe says. “I’ve always wanted to get to know him better.”\r\n\r\nThe smile that Zhongli gives him is almost radiant. He stands, passing through Childe, so close he catches the scent of incense and sandalwood. \r\n\r\n“I will take you up on that invitation one day then,” Zhongli says. \r\n\r\nWatching the gentle sway of his hair, Childe follows him into the lounge. They haven’t spoken about the spar at all. If it weren’t for the singed ends of Zhongli’s coat, Childe would think it was all a figment of his imagination. \r\n\r\nSpeaking of which… He’ll have to get Zhongli a new coat. Surely there’s a tailor here in Liyue who can replicate it.\r\n\r\n“About earlier…” Childe rubs the back of his neck, his voice trailing off as Zhongli looks over his shoulder to stare at him. “I’m sorry if I went too far. Actually, I should apologise for last night too.”\r\n\r\nZhongli turns to him and folds his arms. There’s no sign of any anger on his face, although it’s not like Childe expected that. In all the time he’s known Zhongli, he doesn’t think he’s ever seen the consultant lose his temper. He’s not sure if such a thing is even possible. \r\n\r\n“It is all part of our contract,” Zhongli says. “There is no need to apologise.”\r\n\r\nChilde looks away, resisting the urge to frown. Right. That’s correct. He should be relieved that Zhongli is unfazed with everything that’s happened so far. Should be. \r\n\r\nInstead, Childe can’t ignore the ugly weight clawing at the edges of his chest. He slowly takes a deep breath and forces a smile on his face, nodding at Zhongli. \r\n\r\n“Yeah, I know,” he says. “Just making sure.”\r\n\r\nOutside, a strong gust rattles the wooden boards of the window. The storm doesn’t look like it’s calming down any time soon. \r\n\r\n“I hope Mother and Father are okay…” Childe mumbles. His parents picked the worst day to go out for their sudden date. Can you even still watch plays when the weather is this bad? \r\n\r\nJust then, Childe hears the sound of the front door bursting open. He rushes to the hallway, greeted by the sight of his parents soaked head to toe. Within seconds, there’s a huge puddle in the corridor.\r\n\r\n“Mother! Father!” Childe calls. For a second, he’s worried—then his mother starts cackling with laughter and he can only stare at her in confusion. “What’s so funny?”\r\n\r\nShe throws her head back and laughs even louder. Childe glances at Zhongli, who has taken the liberty to carry the huge collection of bags his parents have brought home with them. Childe’s eyes widen. He gave them some Mora to go shopping with, but did they buy everything in Liyue? \r\n\r\nOnce Childe’s mother has calmed down, she takes her coat off and hands it to him. \r\n\r\n“Your father suggested we run back here before the storm gets worse, but how am I supposed to run with these shoes?” She lifts her leg up to show him the tallest pair of heels he’s ever seen in his life. He could probably stab someone with those. “So, he decided to carry me and sprint back here!”\r\n\r\nChilde looks at his dad, and then towards the dozen bags Zhongli is now carrying. \r\n\r\nHis father laughs, holding his back. “I overestimated myself. Seems like my body’s not as fit as it used to be.”\r\n\r\nChilde is pretty certain anyone would struggle to carry a grown woman and a dozen shopping bags at the same time, all the while running through a storm. \r\n\r\n“I shouldn’t be laughing at this,” his mother says, still laughing. “I think he’s pulled a muscle.”\r\n\r\nChilde shakes his head and lets out a chuckle of his own. “Please sit down. I’ll get the fireplace ready. And what is all this?” He gestures to the bags Zhongli is holding. “Did you two buy half of Liyue’s market stock?”\r\n\r\n“They’re all presents for Tonia’s birthday, of course,” his father says. “Don’t tell me you’ve forgotten?”\r\n\r\n“Of course not,” he quickly answers. \r\n\r\nChilde knew it was her birthday soon. Before the fake relationship, he’d been planning on sending a large crate full of toys and clothes for her. Ever since his family arrived in Liyue, he’d been too caught up in the whole mess to realise how fast her birthday was approaching. \r\n\r\nIt shouldn’t be any problem. With Tonia here, he can give her a better present than a crate full of toys and clothes. \r\n\r\nAll of them settle by the fireplace once Childe’s parents are dried and the gifts they bought for Tonia are safely hidden away from her curious eyes. Childe sits next to Zhongli, muttering a soft thanks when the consultant offers him a cup of tea. \r\n\r\nThen, he throws caution to the wind and leans against Zhongli, laying his head on his shoulder. Childe feels him stiffen for the shortest of seconds, enough for him to think this was a bad idea, oh shit—\r\n\r\nZhongli wraps an arm around his shoulder and pulls him closer, launching his pulse to unhealthy heights. \r\n\r\nAs expected, his parents are staring at them like they’ve just seen an oasis in a desert. Childe takes a sip from his cup and hopes it hides the blush spreading through his face. Please.\r\n\r\nBy some sort of miracle, his mother chooses mercy and doesn’t comment on it. Instead, she faces Zhongli and beams at him. “Mr. Zhongli, we watched one of Ms. Yun’s plays as you suggested. She’s very good.”\r\n\r\nZhongli nods. Every movement he makes sends the scent of sandalwood and incense spinning in Childe’s head. He breathes it in, feeling dizzy. \r\n\r\n“Yes, she is one of the best performers here in Liyue. Watching her plays during the evening has become a regular occurrence for me.”\r\n\r\n“I watched her once with you, didn’t I?” Childe looks up at him. Big mistake because the first thing he lays eyes on are Zhongli’s lips. Which are dangerously close. \r\n\r\nZhongli meets his gaze. Childe swears he feels his arm tighten around him. “Yes, you did. You said the play needed more fighting in it and I had to stop you from joining the stage.”\r\n\r\n“Oh yeah, I remember now.” He smirks. “Well, it did need a bit more action.”\r\n\r\n“It was a romantic play.”\r\n\r\n“Romance can have some action too…” Childe shrugs, fixing his eyes on his cup of tea instead. If Zhongli keeps looking at him like that, he doesn’t think his heart is going to survive. \r\n\r\nAnother gust of wind sends the windows rattling. Childe looks outside and sees nothing but pitch black skies. “That storm doesn’t look like it’s going to end any time soon.”\r\n\r\nZhongli sits up. To Childe’s disappointment, he unwinds his arm around him. \r\n\r\n“I ought to return to the parlour.”\r\n\r\n“In this weather? Nonsense!” Childe’s father says.\r\n\r\n“Yes, he’s right,” his mother agrees, nodding enthusiastically. “You are welcome to stay over for the night, Mr. Zhongli.”\r\n\r\nChilde blinks. “He is?”\r\n\r\nIn less than a second, his mother throws him a disapproving look that sends Childe back to his days as a kid.\r\n\r\n“Ajax, are you going to allow Mr. Zhongli to walk out in that storm? He might get sick!”\r\n\r\nZhongli slowly shakes his head. “The funeral parlour is not too far away, and I rarely get sick…”\r\n\r\n“Oh, no, no, dear. I’m sure Ajax wouldn’t mind it if you stayed over. What kind of fiancé—”\r\n\r\nChilde sighs. “Mother, I’ve told you many times we’re not—”\r\n\r\n“—would Ajax be if he let you leave in this weather?”\r\n\r\nAll eyes turn to him. It takes all of his mental strength not to let out a defeated groan. Ruthless. His parents are truly ruthless. \r\n\r\nChilde turns to Zhongli, smiling as wide as he can. “Mother’s right. You simply must stay, Zhongli.”\r\n\r\nHe sinks back into the couch and drinks the rest of his tea, trying his best to ignore the triumphant look on his mother’s face. \r\n\r\nHis father laughs. “You can finally put that large bed of yours to good use, Ajax.”\r\n\r\nChilde promptly spits out his tea. “Father!”\r\n\r\n“Gavriil, you’ve made him as red as a tomato!” His mother cackles so loud he’s sure Tonia, Teucer, and Anthon are probably awake by now. \r\n\r\nRuthless! Beyond ruthless! Childe grabs Zhongli’s wrist and drags him out of the lounge. By the time they’re in his bedroom, he can still hear his parents laughing at the top of their lungs. At this point, Childe begs the ground to swallow him whole and take him back to the Abyss. He’ll take on fighting monstrous beasts from another world if it meant his parents wouldn’t ever make jokes like that again.\r\n\r\nChilde bangs his head against the door. “Archons, my parents are determined to make this more difficult than it has to be.”\r\n\r\n“If it makes you uncomfortable, I can insist on leaving.”\r\n\r\nHe turns to Zhongli, realising he’s still holding his wrist. Childe quickly lets go and steps back. “No, no. It’s not that… I just… Eh, it doesn’t matter. Are you okay with staying?”\r\n\r\nChilde watches as Zhongli scans his room, as if taking it in. There isn’t much to see in the first place; Childe isn’t the type to fill his surroundings with sentimental items. As such, his room is barren, save for the stack of paperwork strewn all over his desk… which reminds him that he has a few letters he hasn’t replied to yet. \r\n\r\n“If your parents insist I should stay, then they will become suspicious if we are strongly against that idea,” Zhongli says.\r\n\r\nRight. Of course. Childe can only nod at that. Not knowing what else to say, he walks over to his desk and sifts through the letters in search of any he’d need to quickly respond to. Scaramouche… He’ll… save that for another day. Or another week. That midget’s off to Inazuma by now anyway; what could he possibly want from Childe? There’s a few letters from La Signora too, but Childe skims through the contents and decides they’re not worth a response. At least one of the letters is just her insulting him for three paragraphs. Hmm. Maybe he’ll write back with a similar letter of his own when he’s feeling particularly petty.\r\n\r\nOh, and one letter from Pulcinella. He quickly reads through that, grimacing as he reaches the end. It was inevitable, but the Harbingers have heard about the news of his family staying in Liyue. While Pulcinella’s letter remains formal, Childe does not miss the hidden warning underneath his polite words. He’s allowed to keep his family here as long he doesn’t let it distract him from his duties as a Harbinger. \r\n\r\nChilde sighs. No distractions. As if the biggest distraction in his entire life isn’t currently in his room right this very second. \r\n\r\n“Is something the matter?”\r\n\r\nSpeak of the devil… \r\n\r\nChilde turns around and sees that Zhongli is sitting at the edge of his bed, an other-worldly presence that looks out of place in this room. \r\n\r\n“Everything’s fine,” Childe says. “I’ll get you some clothes you can change into. We’re about the same size…”\r\n\r\nTen minutes later, Childe deeply regrets this. How is it possible for one man to look that good? He’s so used to seeing Zhongli wearing several layers of clothes that it doesn’t feel right to see him only wearing a silk shirt and pants. \r\n\r\nChilde tries, and fails, to stop staring. Zhongli has set his hair loose and rubbed the makeup off his eyes, and yet he still manages to look like a famous model. The shirt is a bit loose on him, allowing Childe a glimpse of his collarbones… Shit, this is the most skin he’s ever seen on Zhongli. He can even see his ankles. Is this allowed? Childe swears this is bordering on sacrilege.\r\n\r\n“May I wear this?” Zhongli asks, completely unaware of the downfall of Childe’s sanity. He lifts a silken black robe, waving it slightly. \r\n\r\nChilde nods, unable to formulate anything coherent.\r\n\r\nZhongli slips the robe on and smooths down its nonexistent creases. The combination of the black robe along with the crimson pajamas is a good look on him. \r\n\r\n“You look…” Childe swallows down the dry lump in his throat. Zhongli stares at him, waiting. “Comfortable.”\r\n\r\nVery smooth, his asshole of a brain praises him. Ignoring it, Childe quickly grabs a pillow and a blanket for himself, eager to sleep these thoughts away. If he can sleep at all, that is. \r\n\r\n“You can take the bed, by the way,” he says. “I’ll sleep on the floor.”\r\n\r\n“That is unnecessary. There is enough room for the both of us here.”\r\n\r\nChilde squints at Zhongli, who is once again sitting at the edge of the bed. He frowns back at him, golden eyes almost glowing in the near darkness. \r\n\r\n“I know, but…”\r\n\r\nZhongli reaches for the pillow in his arms, slowly prying it from his grasp. “Your parents will grow suspicious if they find you sleeping on the floor rather than with me.”\r\n\r\n“I should hope they value my privacy enough to not barge into my bedroom…” Childe mutters. He spares one last glance at the floor and groans. “But you’re right.”\r\n\r\nThis is going to be a long night. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n“Your parents are interesting.”\r\n\r\nHalf an hour of staring at the ceiling and failing to sleep had been painfully awkward, to say the least. Childe is almost glad to hear Zhongli’s voice breaking the silence. He turns to his side, searching for Zhongli’s face in the darkness. He sees it as a faint outline against the amber glow of the candles, too dark to fathom his expression but enough to know that those golden eyes are piercing into him. \r\n\r\nChilde whispers into the dark: “What do you mean by that?”\r\n\r\nHe does not get an answer straight away. Waiting, he watches the faint glow of the candles dance along Zhongli’s jaw. This bed is large enough to fit both of them, yet with Zhongli here it feels as if Childe is close to suffocating. When he breathes, all he smells is sandalwood and incense, the fresh scent of earth after rain. Zhongli. \r\n\r\nHe breathes again; in, out, in, out, until his eyes adjust to the darkness and he can see Zhongli is watching him. \r\n\r\n“I am still struggling to understand the complexities of human emotion,” Zhongli says after a while. “I know of happiness and anger, loss… Those are emotions that humans often show freely and you are able to recognise it from their faces. But there are some emotions that are not as obvious.”\r\n\r\nChilde gulps. “Like what?”\r\n\r\n“Love.”\r\n\r\n“...Huh.”\r\n\r\nHe hears Zhongli sigh, stirring the blanket over them so it brushes Childe’s leg. \r\n\r\n“Over the years, I have learnt that humans use love to convey their appreciation for many things, be it money, food, or friendship, but when it comes to romantic love… It seems that is a much deeper level, something which is quite revered in stories or plays. I used to wonder what made it so special.”\r\n\r\nChilde remains silent. He’s not sure how to respond, or why exactly Zhongli is bringing this up. \r\n\r\nAs if sensing his uncertainty, Zhongli speaks on. “Even with my limited understanding of it, I can see that your parents are very much in love. Their happiness radiates the room.”\r\n\r\nChilde lets out a quiet laugh. “Yeah… They\'ve always been like that. I think that\'s why my mother is so obsessed with the idea of us getting married. She probably wants the same for me.”\r\n\r\nHe thinks he sees Zhongli’s eyebrows furrow. It’s hard to tell in the shadows. “You don’t sound enthusiastic about that. Does the idea of marriage not appeal to you?”\r\n\r\nChilde shrugs. “Never cared for it. It\'s as you say: I never knew what made it so special either. It doesn’t feel like a life that could belong to me.”\r\n\r\n“Have you never felt love before?”\r\n\r\n“I love my family, but as for romantic love…” Childe pauses. “I don\'t think so.”\r\n\r\n“Hmm.”\r\n\r\n“...Have you?” Childe asks, remembering what Venti had said. Guizhong. If Zhongli has ever loved anyone, then surely it would be her?\r\n\r\nZhongli moves once again, and this time, Childe feels their legs bump into each other. He almost shifts away, in case Zhongli would prefer some space, but he stops himself. He’s not sure if he wants to move away. Or if he can. \r\n\r\nSo, he stays in place and hopes Zhongli can’t hear how loud his heart is hammering against his ribs. \r\n\r\n“I… don\'t even know what it is exactly meant to feel like,” Zhongli says, his voice so low it sends pinpricks up Childe’s arms. “I am aware that it’s supposed to make you feel happiness… But I also know it makes you feel desire.”\r\n\r\nChilde doesn’t realise he’s let out of a breath of relief until it escapes him. He’d been certain that Guizhong was… \r\n\r\nNo. Why does that even matter? Why is he thinking about such things? \r\n\r\nHe shoves that topic aside and thinks back on Zhongli’s words. \r\n\r\n“Desire and love aren\'t always synonymous, you know,” he says. “You can feel a desire for someone you barely know. Sometimes, it can just be… a reaction.”\r\n\r\n“What do you mean?”\r\n\r\n“You said that love can make you feel desire, and that\'s true… But you can still want someone without understanding any of what you\'re feeling.”\r\n\r\nChilde does not know why he’s saying this all of a sudden. He’s never felt romantically attracted to anyone before, not even close. He has slept with people in the past, but it never led to anything more and nor did he want it to. Even then, he barely counts those as anything close to desire. Distraction, maybe. A result of boredom. \r\n\r\nHe finds Zhongli’s eyes in the darkness. “Have you ever felt that? Desire?”\r\n\r\nChilde’s treading on dangerous ground here. The only sensible part of his brain is telling him to stop this conversation before he ends up regretting it. Unfortunately, the rest of him isn’t listening to that voice. Instead, he waits for Zhongli’s answer with bated breath. \r\n\r\n“I… feel things, but it is difficult to understand what they are. I only know that I feel emotions which are positive, or negative, but labelling them is difficult,” Zhongli lets out what sounds like a quiet sigh. “I have dedicated all of my existence to contracts, but emotions cannot be held by such.”\r\n\r\nChilde can’t help but smile at this. He doesn’t think he’s ever heard Zhongli sounds so uncertain before.  \r\n\r\n“Even humans have a hard time putting a label on their own emotions, xiansheng. It\'s as you say: we know if it makes us feel good or not, but we don\'t always know what the feeling is, or why we\'re feeling that.” He reaches over to pat Zhongli on his arm. “Sounds pretty human to me.”\r\n\r\nZhongli hums. “Then I suppose I am adjusting to mortal life better than I imagined.”\r\n\r\nThey fall into silence. The sound of rain has long stopped and night is peaceful once more. It’s quiet, too quiet. Empty. Childe turns to lay on his back, staring up at the ceiling. He has a feeling he’ll be staring at this all night. \r\n\r\n“What is… desire supposed to feel like?”\r\n\r\nChilde freezes. Now this conversation really is diving into dangerous territory. He keeps his gaze pinned on the ceiling despite knowing that Zhongli is staring at him, waiting. \r\n\r\n“It… makes you want more,” he chokes out. “You feel like you can’t control yourself and you don’t understand why you feel like this, but… you just want that person.”\r\n\r\n“...I see.”\r\n\r\nChilde doesn’t dare look at Zhongli, and nor does he dare entertain the idea of asking if Zhongli has ever felt like that. \r\n\r\nHe also avoids thinking about the fact that maybe, just maybe, that description he gave hits a bit closer to home than he’d like it to. \r\n\r\n“We should get some sleep,” Childe quickly says. He turns to the other side, making sure his back is facing Zhongli, and scowls into the darkness. Sleep feels like an impossible task tonight. \r\n\r\n“Yes,” he hears Zhongli saying. “Goodnight, Childe.”\r\n\r\n“Goodnight, xiansheng.”\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAfter what feels like two hours of staring into the darkness, Childe concludes there is no way he is getting any sleep tonight. Making sure not to wake Zhongli up, he shuffles out of the blankets and fumbles around for his slippers. \r\n\r\nZhongli remains fast asleep. Childe can’t resist staring at him before he goes. Candlelight paints the edges of his figure and basks him in an amber glow, mixing with the onyx ripples of his silken robe. His chest rises and falls with each breath, long hair fanning around the blanket like dark strokes of paint on canvas. \r\n\r\nChilde leans across the bed and gently moves a strand of Zhongli’s hair away from his face. As if sensing him, the ex-Archon leans closer and sighs. \r\n\r\nHe holds his breath, not daring to risk any sound. His gaze moves down to Zhongli’s parted lips. \r\n\r\nNo. \r\n\r\nHe clenches his jaw and rips his hand away. Stop it, stop it, stop it, stop it, he chants in his head as he forces some distance between them. Without sparing another look at Zhongli, he crosses the other side of the room. \r\n\r\nChilde needs to breathe. He throws open the window and climbs out, bracing himself against the sudden gust of wind that greets him. The storm is no more; the only remnant left of it is the cold breeze that bites into his skin and the scent of petrichor amidst the air. \r\n\r\nWith his apartment situated in one of the top floors of the guesthouse, his bedroom window leads to a set of rooftops that overlook the front harbour. It’s become a habit for Childe to climb out of his window and admire the view of the city from above.\r\n\r\nLiyue is a beautiful city, but it is even more breathtaking past sunset. From this distance, every lantern glows like an amber beacon in the vermilion streets. Even late at night, Liyue is alive with business; there are people cheering in the bars, stories being told in the tea houses, orders being shouted from across the pier where its men work late into the night. \r\n\r\nChilde sits at the edge of the rooftop and listens. He’s been in Liyue for so long that he can tell who is shouting from the harbour. Amidst the noise, he also spots the lone figure of a Fatui guard watching the sea from the front of the harbour. Vlad, he thinks his name is, and he only knows this because Childe remembers this particular guard had been asking to be sent back to Snezhnaya—\r\n\r\nThe sound of footsteps yank him away from his thoughts. He looks up as Zhongli sits next to him.\r\n\r\n“Sorry,” Childe says. “Did I wake you?”\r\n\r\nZhongli shakes his head. “The view here is lovely.”\r\n\r\n“Yeah. I like sitting out here at night and just watching the city.”\r\n\r\nZhongli tilts his head at him. “Are you not tired?”\r\n\r\nYes, Childe wants to say. But I can’t sleep because you’re there.\r\n\r\n“Nope, not really,” he lies. \r\n\r\nHe gazes up at the sky and wonders when the sun will rise. With Zhongli next to him, it feels like tonight is never-ending. \r\n\r\nWhat’s wrong with him? He’s always spent time with Zhongli, but he has never felt this restless before. Now, it feels like all of his senses are attuned to the god, sending his thoughts running round and round in circles. \r\n\r\nHe doesn’t want to think. Whenever he thinks, it ends up leading him to a spiral of doubts and emotions he can\'t understand. Or he doesn\'t want to understand. \r\n\r\nFrustrated, Childe stands up. \r\n\r\n“Xiansheng… Fight me again. Now.”\r\n\r\nZhongli blinks up at him, clearly taken aback. “Now?”\r\n\r\n“Because of the kids, we were holding ourselves back earlier, so let’s have a rematch.”\r\n\r\n“This is hardly the right time and place.”\r\n\r\n“Nonsense! A fight can happen anywhere!”\r\n\r\nNarrowing his eyes, Zhongli looks down at the harbour. “People will see us. It will be disruptive if we use our visions this late at night.”\r\n\r\nHe has a point, but Childe has never been one to let something like that stop him from a fight. He quickly climbs back into his bedroom and returns with a pair of wooden spears. \r\n\r\n“Here,” he says, throwing one of them to Zhongli. “Then no visions. We fight with just weapons; the good old fashioned way.”\r\n\r\nZhongli stands, spinning the spear in his hand. “What is this sudden fixation with wishing to fight me?”\r\n\r\n“Oh, xiansheng, you know nothing gets my blood pumping more than a good fight, and what better opponent to have than an ex-god?” Childe grins, leading Zhongli to another set of rooftops. Here, there is more space for them to freely move. Obviously, it is not as spacious as an open field, but it will do. \r\n\r\nHe stands on one end of the roof while Zhongli is on the other. From there, the full moon floats behind the ex-Archon, submerging him in silver. \r\n\r\n“This will be the last spar,” Zhongli says, his words final. “Do not ask me again.”\r\n\r\nChilde grips his weapon. “Guess we’ll have to make it a good one then.”\r\n\r\nHe lunges, and the clash of spears sends his pulse kicking once again. In an instant, they meet each parry, each strike, each sweep, synchronised in perfect chorus. The howling of the wind joins them, brushing across Childe’s hair and bare arms as the two weave past each other.\r\n\r\nIt becomes a dance of sorts; Childe stabs forward and Zhongli side-steps away, his movements lithe, graceful. Before he can blink, the tip of a spear hurtles into his vision and Childe throws himself back, dodging in time. He smirks, regaining his balance while Zhongli summons his weapon back to his side. \r\n\r\nThey leap into each other, clashing in mid-air. As they fall back into their flurry of blows, Childe feints to the side, watching as Zhongli follows his movement. When he sees the ex-Archon move, he sweeps his spear downwards, intent on catching the other’s legs. \r\n\r\nNonetheless, Zhongli is smart; he should have known that. He dodges, hardly fazed, and sends a kick driving straight into Childe’s chest. It’s so unexpected, so sudden, that Childe staggers, the air in his lungs knocked back. Zhongli descends on him with a whirlwind of jabs, each one faster than the last. \r\n\r\nChilde dodges, or he tries to. As he struggles to regain momentum of the battle, he catches sight of Zhongli encased by the backdrop of moonlight, and it’s as if everything slows to a stop. \r\n\r\nZhongli twists his spear and strikes the blunt end into his gut. Time moves once again and Childe falls into a heap on the rooftop. \r\n\r\nPain spreads through every limb in his body, burning in the core of his stomach where Zhongli had struck him. His head aches, the world is spinning, and the acknowledgement of defeat is heavy in his heart. \r\n\r\nZhongli stands before him, his obsidian robes billowing against the large moon that seems to swallow him whole. His eyes are as bright and gold as the lanterns around Liyue and Childe stares back, transfixed. He doesn’t dare move, not even when Zhongli points the tip of his spear to his neck. \r\n\r\nHe trails it up his throat, so close that Childe feels the blunt blade tickle against his skin. He gulps. \r\n\r\nZhongli keeps his eyes on him as he nudges Childe’s chin up.\r\n\r\n“Do you yield?” he asks. \r\n\r\nChilde’s heart is beating so hard he thinks he\'s going to be sick. His chest is heaving with exhaustion, excitement, adrenaline, and the unmistakable feeling that he wants more, needs more. He wants to take his spear and fight on, he wants to grab Zhongli and push him into the ground, he wants to bury his face into his neck and taste him again, he wants to devour him—\r\n\r\nAnd he’s hard. Very hard. \r\n\r\nWith that startling realisation, he says the only thing he can think of:\r\n\r\n“Shit.”', 'set_in_stone.jpg', '2021-04-25 22:01:32.999941', '2021-04-26 10:15:29.467130', '0', '1', 'set_in_stone_03', '1', '2', 'Set in Stone');
INSERT INTO `sueed_article` VALUES ('4', 'Set in Stone 04', 'the same with 01', 'Chapter 4: New Arrangements\r\n\r\nThere was no denying it. Childe is sporting a full on boner after being beaten up by Zhongli, which, by the way, he’d be more gutted about if he could actually focus on his defeat. \r\n\r\nAlas, he cannot. Instead, he’s about to have a mid-life crisis on top of this roof. There is no way he can deny his attraction for Zhongli now, not when there’s physical proof of it in the form of his stupid dick currently defying gravity. \r\n\r\nShit. \r\n\r\nChilde groans and forces himself to sit up, not so subtly throwing an arm over his crotch in a futile attempt to hide it. \r\n\r\n“Okay, okay, you win for tonight,” he chokes out, unable to look at Zhongli in the eyes. \r\n\r\nSo what if he’s hard? He’s always lived for battles and gotten high off the adrenaline. Granted, he’s never actually gotten hard from a battle before, but there’s a first time for everyone… \r\n\r\nThe fact that it’s Zhongli does not help either. He’s gone and gotten himself attracted to the damn ex-Archon. \r\n\r\nBut that’s it… It’s only an attraction. That’s fine. Childe can deal with that. Zhongli is very attractive; he’d be surprised if he wasn’t the least bit drawn to him. It shouldn’t be any surprise that being around the consultant so much has led to Childe perhaps wanting to sleep with him. \r\n\r\nFuck. \r\n\r\nGet it together, the rational part of his brain speaks up. Why is this such a big deal? There’s nothing wrong with wanting to have sex with someone, and it’s not like there’s anything going on with you and Zhongli…\r\n\r\nRight. This is just a physical attraction. Nothing more. \r\n\r\nDon’t even go there. Remember the contract.\r\n\r\nUgh. How could he forget? Even if he wanted to, there’s no way Zhongli would ever… No. No, he’s not even going to go there. He can’t entertain that idea. \r\n\r\nChilde sighs, finally mustering the courage to turn to the man in question. Zhongli remains where he’s standing, still holding his spear, although he’s no longer pointing it at Childe’s throat. \r\n\r\nGods, Childe hopes Zhongli hasn’t noticed his boner. \r\n\r\nZhongli steps back, tilting his head slightly. “You seem to be physically aroused.”\r\n\r\nNever mind. \r\n\r\nChilde jolts as if he’s been physically struck. He quickly looks away, scouring through his head for any excuse that could explain why his dick is still hard this very moment. \r\n\r\nHe comes up with nothing. The only thought going through his head right now is: shit shit shit shit shit shit.\r\n\r\n“I-I…” Fuck. Sighing, Childe runs a hand through his hair and shakes his head. There’s no point in lying to someone like Zhongli. “Don’t think too much of it, xiansheng. Let’s just go to sleep—”\r\n\r\n“Would you like help in relieving it?”\r\n\r\nChilde blinks. He looks up and blinks again, several times, while watching Zhongli’s impassive face. Then, his words sink in. \r\n\r\n“What?” Childe says. “What?”\r\n\r\nIn true Zhongli fashion, his expression doesn’t change at all. He only nods at Childe. “Is that not what is typically done in this situation? If one is aroused, they will pleasure themselves to—”\r\n\r\n“Yeah, yeah, I know, but why are you offering to help?”\r\n\r\nThat seems to break some emotion onto Zhongli’s face. For a second, his brows furrow into the tiniest frown before it disappears. “This is still within our contract.”\r\n\r\n“What?”\r\n\r\n“Our contract states that there are to be no feelings or complications within this fake relationship, and as you stated earlier, experiencing desire does not necessarily involve feelings as well. Therefore, if we continue with that, then it will still work alongside our contract.”\r\n\r\n...What?\r\n\r\nChilde is so lost that he’s pretty sure his boner has already died. He replays what Zhongli said in his head, going through each word as slowly as he can. As expected of Zhongli, he’s discussing something like this so casually as if they’re talking about the weather. Childe shouldn’t be surprised at all, but… \r\n\r\nHe sits up and scratches his head. “Are you… Are you suggesting that we become friends with benefits?”\r\n\r\n“I’m... not familiar with that term.”\r\n\r\nChilde sighs  again. Why are they even having this conversation? How did they end up talking about this and why why why is Zhongli suggesting it of all things? \r\n\r\nTsaritsa… No, this is definitely something Childe didn’t need to start thinking about. \r\n\r\n“No… That’s… This… No. We shouldn’t. I’m not even sure if you know what you’re suggesting, xiansheng.”\r\n\r\nZhongli narrows his eyes slightly. “I’m suggesting that we enter a sexual arrangement in order to relieve mutual desires, under the pretense that we do not let emotions break our contract. You were the one who proposed that desire does not often lead to—”\r\n\r\n“I know what I said! But why are you okay with that?” Childe interrupts, surprised by the sudden volume of his own voice. He takes a deep breath and swears under his breath. Shit. \r\n\r\nHe’s not the only one who’s shocked. Zhongli stares at him with wide eyes. “I… Have I said something to upset you?”\r\n\r\nChilde automatically shakes his head, pushing himself up to his feet and staring out towards the view of Liyue’s harbour underneath them. He can feel Zhongli’s eyes on him, waiting for a verbal response. \r\n\r\nFuck, he thinks. He is upset. For some reason, having to listen to Zhongli casually talk about something like this as if it barely matters isn’t sitting well with him. \r\n\r\nBut does it really matter? It’s not like Childe hasn’t had casual sex before. He’s not beyond the idea of sleeping with someone and disregarding it the next day.\r\n\r\nFuck, he thinks again. There’s only one reason why this bothers him, and he doesn’t want to dwell on it. He can’t. \r\n\r\n“No, no. I don’t even know why I’m…” He groans and shakes his head again, still unable to look at Zhongli. “Ugh, it doesn’t matter. Let’s just forget about this, okay?”\r\n\r\n“…If that is what you wish.”\r\n\r\nChilde doesn’t wait for Zhongli to follow him. He climbs back into his room and throws himself into bed, desperately hoping he can sleep this off and forget all about it in the morning. \r\n\r\nObviously that’s impossible, and to no one’s surprise, Childe’s traitorous brain is conjuring images of Zhongli offering to relieve him instead. At this point, Childe will gladly bash his head against a wall if it’s going to knock him out and put an end to this night. \r\n\r\nHe hears Zhongli stir next to him. \r\n\r\n“I am sorry for assuming that…” \r\n\r\nChilde turns to face the consultant. He’s so close that their knees bump and the scent of flowers and incense suffocates Childe. He’s going to be smelling Zhongli on his pillows for the rest of the week, he thinks. \r\n\r\n“Xiansheng, it’s fine,” Childe reassures. “You don’t even need to apologise for anything.”\r\n\r\n“I have clearly made you upset.”\r\n\r\n“I’m not upset.” Much.\r\n\r\nChilde pauses. He studies Zhongli’s face for a bit, debating on whether he should say what’s currently on his mind. In the end, he takes the risk and lowers his voice to a whisper.  \r\n\r\n“I’d be lying if the proposition didn’t intrigue me.”\r\n\r\nZhongli’s eyebrows raise ever so slightly. “Oh.”\r\n\r\nThere’s an excruciating second where both of them glance down at each other’s lips at the same time. Childe almost leans in then—no, in fact, he does. His head tilts down and he holds his breath, picturing the moment when he finally closes the distance between them and pushes Zhongli against the sheets. \r\n\r\nHe could. He wants to. He could accept Zhongli’s earlier proposition and see where that leads. The choice is within his grasp and all he has to do is lean in and kiss Zhongli. They can pretend that none of this happened once the sun rises tomorrow. \r\n\r\nHe… \r\n\r\nChilde swallows the lump stuck in his throat. That’s the problem though. He can’t. If anything happened between him and Zhongli, Childe won’t be able to forget about it. \r\n\r\nHe winces. He pushes himself back until he has space to breathe.\r\n\r\n“But it’s best if we don’t go there,” Childe says. “We should get some sleep.”\r\n\r\nSlowly, Zhongli nods. “Goodnight, Childe.”\r\n\r\nChilde turns to the other side and squeezes his eyes shut, blocking out the voice in his head telling him to go back to Zhongli and fuck him silly. \r\n\r\nStupid horny thoughts. Stupid dick. Stupid contract. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nTartaglia,\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nI sincerely hope you’re not wreaking havoc where you are, although considering it’s you… Whatever. Just don’t do anything to embarrass the Tsaritsa any more than you already have.\r\n\r\nI’ve heard news that your family is now in Liyue with you. Don’t get distracted with trivial matters. You’re not there on a holiday.\r\n\r\nSo far, we haven’t received any new leads regarding the other Archons. For now, stay where you are and wait for further instructions when we need you. Keep an eye on Morax in case he does anything suspicious. \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nScaramouche\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nChilde rolls his eyes and waves the letter in front of a candle, watching as the corners catch fire. What was even the point of Scaramouche sending him this when Pulcinella already wrote one that literally said the same thing? \r\n\r\nScaramouche liked the sound of his own voice too much, and apparently, that translated into writing as well. \r\n\r\nBefore the letter disintegrates into ashes, Childe catches sight of the last paragraph. For now, stay where you are and wait for further instructions when we need you. \r\n\r\nIt’s a good reminder to himself that he won’t be in Liyue forever. As much as he’s grown attached to this place, he can’t stay here. He has his loyalties to uphold and his own home to return to.\r\n\r\nNevertheless, he can’t stop himself from thinking about a certain ex-Geo Archon. \r\n\r\nThree days. It’s been three days since that happened. When Childe woke up the next day, Zhongli was already gone and he couldn’t help but feel like he’d been thrown aside after a one night stand—except no sex actually happened, and Zhongli probably doesn’t even know what the term ‘one night stand’ means. \r\n\r\nUgh, what a mess. \r\n\r\nAnd so, since he’s determined not to delve further into whatever happened between him and Zhongli, Childe has been busying himself with work. Specifically, he’s been debt collecting and taking his frustrations out on the poor idiots who try to avoid paying their loans. He finds out very quickly that it’s a good stress reliever. Fun, even.\r\n\r\nHe’s not exactly avoiding Zhongli, but he’s not seeking him out either. Luckily, his family hasn’t insisted on seeing his fake boyfriend for a while. Part of Childe hopes that this means they’ve stopped obsessing over it and they won’t have to do anything else with this fake relationship. \r\n\r\nThe other part… Well, the other part is stupid because it’s gutted about the fact he won’t need a reason to see Zhongli. \r\n\r\nNot that he ever needed a reason to see Zhongli to begin with… Still, he can’t ignore the fact that things are different now. No complications or feelings, my ass, he bitterly thinks. Childe has really dug himself into a hole this time. \r\n\r\nFucking Tsaritsa, he’s started thinking about it again. No, this won’t do. He needs to distract himself. More debt collecting is in order today, or maybe he should find Lumine and see if she needs help beating up anyone…\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nLumine is nowhere to be found in Liyue. Childe suspects the strange traveller is either in Mondstadt, or she’s flinging herself down more waterfalls to deliver food to people. Or both. Lumine did tell him once that she sometimes delivers food for a restaurant owner named Sara there. Why her customers are waiting by waterfalls or cliffs, Childe will never know. \r\n\r\nWell, since Lumine isn’t around for Childe to pester, it looks like he’ll just collect more debts today. \r\n\r\n“How’s my favourite Northland Bank receptionist?” Childe says as soon as he enters the bank. \r\n\r\nEkaterina glances up at him from her desk. “Sir, I am the only Northland Bank receptionist.”\r\n\r\nHe winks at her. “And that’s why we love you.”\r\n\r\nShe sighs and resumes flickering through the pile of papers in front of her. Come to think of it, it’s a very large pile of papers and Childe doesn’t think he’s ever seen the receptionist look so stressed before. \r\n\r\nHe stops by her desk. It\'s only now that he notices there are a number of Fatui recruits within the bank. All of them seem to be on edge, muttering amongst each other. Usually, they try not to station too many Fatui inside the bank; while Northland Bank is becoming more and more popular with the Liyuens, many of them are still wary of the Fatui. \r\n\r\nFortunately, there are no customers inside the bank at this time, but it’s obvious now that something is amiss. \r\n\r\n“What’s wrong?” Childe asks. \r\n\r\n“It’s strange. Our records from last month came back… There’s been large withdrawals being made, but no records of who is taking the Mora, or where it’s going.”\r\n\r\nEkaterina slides a sheet to him and Childe takes a brief second to skim through it. As she explained, there are large deductions of Mora from their vaults. Normally, everything is sourced in their records to keep track of where their money is going; it makes it much easier to hunt down customers when they need to. \r\n\r\nChilde hums to himself, then pushes the sheet back to Ekaterina. “So, what you’re saying is that someone’s been stealing from the bank.”\r\n\r\n“It’s possible but our security is immaculate. I cannot imagine that anyone would be able to breach it.”\r\n\r\nTrue. They have Fatui stationed around the vaults if anyone dared to steal from them. Besides, Childe always thought the rumours surrounding the Northland Bank was enough to scare potential thieves away. He thought wrong. \r\n\r\n“When did this start?”\r\n\r\nEkaterina purses her lips as she trails her finger down the records. “It was happening quite frequently last month… but it’s stopped since last week.” She frowns, leaning closer to the sheet as if it would help make more sense of the numbers. “That’s peculiar. It stopped around the same time we changed the codes for the vault.”\r\n\r\nChilde scratches his head. “Okay, so whoever is stealing from the bank somehow knew our old codes, and now that we’ve changed them, they’ve been unable to steal from us again?”\r\n\r\n“The vaults are very intricate… Not just anyone will be able to unlock them, let alone breach our security.”\r\n\r\nWho could possibly have enough balls to steal from the bank, and not just any bank but a bank controlled by the Fatui? Most of the customers they hunt down almost faint on the spot the moment they see the Fatui have come to collect their debts.\r\n\r\nChilde thinks back on all the people they’ve had to collect debts from. A lot of them are greedy merchants trying to use their loans to expand their business. Although… there’s also those who go to that place.\r\n\r\n“It could be someone from the Pearl Galley again. People there are always using our loans to pay off their visits,” Childe suggests. \r\n\r\nIt’s one of the funniest things Childe remembers about the bank. When the Tsaritsa first sent him to Liyue, it only took a week for him to notice that a lot of their men were being sent to the Galley to dispose of customers. Once he realised the Pearl Galley actually served as both a brothel and a casino, everything suddenly made sense…\r\n\r\n“It’s funny that you should mention that… There are rumours that there have been two deaths related to the Pearl Galley as of recently.” Ekaterina glances around, as if making sure there are no customers to hear them despite the bank currently being empty. “They were not our doing. It was the escorts who were murdered. The first death was… last week. And the most recent one was yesterday.”\r\n\r\nThat’s… unexpected. “What? You think they\'re linked?”\r\n\r\nThe receptionist shrugs. “Maybe… The deaths started occurring around the time money was no longer being stolen from us. And from the looks of it, the culprit stopped stealing because they are now unable to open our vaults. Perhaps they were using the money to enjoy themselves at the Pearl Galley, but resorted to murdering its escorts once they no longer had the funds to afford them?”\r\n\r\n“Wow.” Childe whistles. “This is why you\'re our favourite Northland Bank receptionist.”\r\n\r\nEkaterina’s lips tug up into a rare smile. “I was under the impression it was because I\'m the only Northland Bank receptionist.”\r\n\r\n“That too.”\r\n\r\nShe laughs under her breath. In less than a second, all signs of emotion disappear from her face and she’s back to being serious. “Of course, the two incidents could be completely unrelated but it is worth looking at.”\r\n\r\n“Okay. Have their bodies been retrieved?”\r\n\r\n“They should be in the Wangsheng Funeral Parlour.”\r\n\r\nOf course they would be. Childe’s thoughts instantly travel to a certain consultant who should be there right now… Looks like he can’t avoid him forever. \r\n\r\nHe nods. “Let me look into this then.”\r\n\r\nBefore he leaves, Ekaterina coughs loudly. Very loudly. “Sir. Please refrain from causing a scene in the Pearl Galley. Discretion is absolutely vital. It is already a miracle you are still able to remain in Liyue after what you did last time.”\r\n\r\nChilde waves a hand, already one foot out of the door. “I’m always discreet.”\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nAs soon as Childe steps into the parlour, he’s greeted by the incarnation of evil—according to almost every Liyuen he comes across, anyway. Then again, they probably say the same for him too. \r\n\r\nHu Tao grins at him from where she’s sitting. He waves at her, scanning the room for any sign of Zhongli. \r\n\r\n“Hello, lover boy. Come to visit your fiancé?”\r\n\r\n“He’s not my… Eh, whatever.” Fiancé, boyfriend, lover… What difference does it make? They’re all fake anyway. “Yes, yes, I have.”\r\n\r\nThe short girl motions towards one of the rooms to his right. “He’s back there examining a new corpse. Don’t distract him too much, and no funny business! I’ve seen that hickey you put on his neck… How scandalous.”\r\n\r\nChilde sincerely hopes he’s not blushing. The shit-eating grin spreading across Hu Tao’s face tells him there’s a possibility that he is. \r\n\r\n“Ugh,” is the only coherent response he can think of. He’s really not well equipped to deal with people teasing him about this fake relationship. \r\n\r\nUnfortunately, Hu Tao is ruthless. She sits up on her chair and smirks into her hands. “Go easy on him, okay? Zhongli may look young but I have a feeling he\'s much older than he lets on…”\r\n\r\nChilde narrows his eyes. Surely she doesn’t know that…?\r\n\r\nHu Tao laughs. “Heh. Just kidding!”\r\n\r\nChilde is starting to understand why even Zhongli’s immaculate patience cannot handle Hu Tao. He sighs, deciding it’s not worth carrying on this conversation. He came here for Fatui business, not to be teased by a girl half his size.\r\n\r\nAs Hu Tao mentioned, Zhongli is examining a corpse when Childe walks into the room. Clearly Childe is the last person Zhongli expected today from the way his eyebrows raise up as soon as he sees him. \r\n\r\nThey stare at each other. Childe was hoping this visit won\'t be awkward at all, and yet the more seconds that pass between them in silence, the more he realises awkwardness might be futile. \r\n\r\nZhongli takes a step forward. “Childe. Good afternoon.”\r\n\r\nChilde forces out a smile. “Hey.” \r\n\r\nHe was supposed to delve right into his investigation, but one look at Zhongli and suddenly his brain has blanked out. The hickey on Zhongli’s neck has faded by now, as if it had never been there to begin with. Childe is ashamed to admit he first reacts to this with disappointment but he quickly squashes those inappropriate thoughts away. \r\n\r\nFor once, Zhongli isn’t wearing his coat—most likely because Childe singed it with his delusion during their spar last time. Shit, Childe was going to get a new coat tailored for him. He had completely forgotten about it.\r\n\r\n“Sorry,” Childe blurts out. “About your coat.”\r\n\r\nZhongli blinks. “My coat?”\r\n\r\n“I burnt it during our spar last time, remember? I was going to get a new one made for you, actually…”\r\n\r\n“Oh.” To Childe’s surprise, Zhongli lets out a short laugh. “There is no need for you to do that.”\r\n\r\nHe turns around and pulls at something draped over a chair. When Childe gets a better look, he sees that it’s Zhongli’s coat, minus the singed ends. \r\n\r\n“I have another one just like it,” Zhongli explains. “I had it made by a travelling tailor who was staying in Liyue for a few months. She suggested that it would be best if I owned two versions, should something happen to the other one…”\r\n\r\nMaybe she just wanted more money out of you—or the person who was paying for you, Childe thinks. Because he’s the best fake boyfriend ever, he doesn’t say it out loud. \r\n\r\n“Therefore, you do not need to get me a new coat,” Zhongli tells him, draping the coat back over his chair. “But the thought is appreciated.”\r\n\r\nChilde nods. “Okay. Um.” Back on track. He was supposed to talk to Zhongli about the corpses, not his wardrobe. “Are you busy?”\r\n\r\n“Hmm. Did you need anything?”\r\n\r\n“This may be an odd question, but have you received corpses from the Pearl Galley recently?”\r\n\r\nZhongli motions towards the body he’d been examining earlier. “This one. Evidently murdered.”\r\n\r\nChilde walks closer, frowning at the corpse before them. The first thing he notices is that their throat is slashed; most likely the cause of their death. The second thing he notices is that it’s not just a slashed throat; the cut is so deep he can see bone underneath. Any deeper and this would be a beheaded body. \r\n\r\nConsidering it’s not beheaded, Childe doubts the killer’s purpose was to cut the throat this deep. Most likely, they weren’t aware of their own strength or they’re used to battles that require more. \r\n\r\n“It\'s just like the other corpse I saw here the other day. That one had their arm cut off. I remember thinking it was impressive since your average citizen can’t do that...” he says. “Whoever is killing these people is experienced in battle.”\r\n\r\nZhongli rubs his chin and stares up, deep in thought. “The other body you are mentioning… That also came from the Pearl Galley.”\r\n\r\n“That… makes sense, actually.”\r\n\r\n“Is there any reason why you are asking about this?”\r\n\r\nChilde contemplates whether he should tell Zhongli or not. Really, he came here to examine the corpses himself, and he is trying to limit his interactions with the consultant until he can shake certain thoughts off his head… \r\n\r\nWell, easier said than done. Now that he’s here, staying away from Zhongli is an impossible task to return to. He naturally gravitates towards Zhongli, already thinking of several questions to catch up with him during their time away from each other. \r\n\r\nNo time for that, he reminds himself. If he’s going to talk with Zhongli, he may as well explain the situation to him… \r\n\r\n“Miss Ekaterina’s theory is plausible, however it is only a theory,” Zhongli says once he’s finished summarising Northland Bank’s current predicament. “If you were to investigate the Pearl Galley, it could be that the murderer is not the thief from the Northland Bank.”\r\n\r\nChilde leans against the table behind him, taking care not to knock over the large pile of books atop it. \r\n\r\n“I know, I know, but it’s the only lead I have,” he says, watching as Zhongli carefully covers the corpse with a sheet. “Besides, an unknown murderer prowling through Liyue… Isn’t that exciting?”\r\n\r\nZhongli glances at him from the corner of his eyes. “That is not the word I would use to describe it,” he mutters, not at all amused. “But if we are to investigate the ship, you will need to be in disguise. Many in the Galley are wary that Fatui are the reason why patrons disappear once they are unable to pay back the rest of their loans. If the thief is indeed within the ship, then your presence may scare them away.”\r\n\r\nHuh. He didn’t think of that. Honestly, Childe’s plan so far has been: \r\n\r\nInvestigate the corpses.\r\nGo to the Galley.\r\nFind the culprit and fight them. \r\nNow that he thinks about it, that’s a very vague plan with a lot of room for error, but he had a similar approach when he was trying to steal Zhongli’s gnosis and that somehow worked out in the end. Childe is never one for elaborate schemes; he likes to dive in head first and fight the people he needs to fight. It works. Usually. \r\n\r\nAnyway, surely it can’t be that difficult to find a killer in a brothel? \r\n\r\n“Good point,” he says, then frowns. “What do you mean ‘we’?”\r\n\r\nZhongli smiles at him. “I will go with you. I am a frequent visitor of the Galley.”\r\n\r\nChilde doesn’t think he heard that properly. \r\n\r\nZhongli… Frequent visitor of the Galley… which is also a brothel...\r\n\r\n“What?”\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n“Wait, brother, we need to take a picture! Smile for the kamera!”\r\n\r\nChilde is attacked by a blazing flash of light before he can even register half of that sentence. While he’s temporarily blind, he hears his siblings giggling amidst the nonstop clicking. Little devils…\r\n\r\nAfter Tonia is finished with her kamera assault, she shows him the pictures; all ten of them with him looking like he’s being attacked by the sun. \r\n\r\n“Mother says she wants to send these pictures to Brother Alek!” Tonia says.\r\n\r\nChilde frowns. First of all, you can barely see his face with how bright the flash is; and secondly… Alek? Childe hasn’t seen his eldest sibling since… since forever. \r\n\r\n“Him? I think the last time I saw him, I was still wearing diapers. Does he even remember me?” he asks, struggling to put a face on his sibling. Alek is ten years older than him; as far as Childe can remember, he was already married with a family of his own when Childe enlisted into the Fatui.\r\n\r\nAnthon nods. “He writes to us almost as much as you do, Brother!”\r\n\r\n“But he never sends us any toys…” Teucer adds with a small pout. \r\n\r\n“He said that if you and Mr. Zhongli ever get married for real, he’ll attend the wedding!” Tonia says. Before Childe can remind them he is not marrying Zhongli, she takes several more pictures. \r\n\r\n“Alright, alright, that’s enough pictures for now,” he says, reaching for the kamera. He’s going to lose his eyesight at this rate. “Zhongli’s waiting for me in the lounge.”\r\n\r\nTheir plan to investigate the Pearl Galley is to be set in motion tonight. As luck would have it, there is an opera viewing later on, which hopefully means more patrons will attend. Since Zhongli is apparently a frequent and highly regarded visitor of the Galley, they don’t need a special invitation. \r\n\r\n(Childe is still in shock over that. Coupled with Zhongli’s casual proposal of being friends with benefits, he’s starting to wonder if Zhongli isn’t as… uptight as he seems to be. Tsaritsa. Just thinking about it is enough to drive him insane. No. No, he should stop thinking about it.)\r\n\r\nHe walks into the lounge and instantly spots his fake boyfriend. A smile makes its way onto his face when he sees the gigantic bouquet of flowers Zhongli is holding, exactly like the first time he met Childe’s family. \r\n\r\n“Thank you,” Childe says, hefting the bouquet into his arms. Archons, this thing is even heavier than the last one. He leans in to kiss Zhongli on the cheek, lingering longer than necessary until the sensible voice inside his head starts yelling at him to pull back. \r\n\r\n“Let me find a vase for that,” Childe’s mother says, popping up in the middle of nowhere to snatch the bouquet from his grasp. \r\n\r\nOnce she leaves, Childe takes a moment to admire how Zhongli looks—and damn, he looks good. As Zhongli suggested, it would be best if Childe wore different clothes for tonight, in order to avoid the patrons from recognising him as being part of the Fatui. At first, Zhongli wanted him to wear a hanfu and Childe tried on many variations of the robes before deciding it would be too difficult to fight in them should they need to. \r\n\r\nIn the end, they decided that wearing a changshan would be the best option. It was a traditional Liyuen dress worn by men, resembling a long tunic; not quite as elaborate as hanfu but at least much easier to move around in. \r\n\r\nThe one Childe is wearing is a rich navy colour, decorated with detailed golden patterns along one side; unlike Zhongli’s, his changshan stops by his waist rather than below his knees, and is paired with black pants. It’s not as comfortable to move around in as his normal attire, but it will do. For obvious reasons, he’s not wearing his Fatui mask tonight. Instead, his hair has been styled by his over-enthusiastic mother and sister, slicked back on one side and his bangs combed away from his eyes for once.\r\n\r\nZhongli told him he would wear something similar, but nothing could have prepared Childe for this. The burgundy changshan he’s wearing fits him like a glove, making it impossible for the Harbinger to ignore how slender his waist is. There are golden patterns adorning the dress in the form of a dragon surrounded by swirling flames, but, really, Childe can barely focus on what the outfit looks like when Zhongli looks amazing in anything. \r\n\r\n“You look... “ Childe swallows, scrambling for a suitable description. “Good.”\r\n\r\nZhongli beams at him. “As do you. The clothes suit you very much.”\r\n\r\nJust then, Childe’s mother materialises between them again. She dusts off Childe’s shoulders and straightens his jacket. \r\n\r\n“He looks very handsome, doesn’t he, Mr. Zhongli?” she says. “Ajax, I love your hair like this… You should style it like this more often; your hair is always such a mess.”\r\n\r\nChilde feigns a distraught expression, clutching his chest. “You wound me, Mother.”\r\n\r\nHis father laughs. “Are you two going on a date?”\r\n\r\nZhongli nods. “Yes, I am taking Ajax to watch an opera with me.”\r\n\r\nAmong other things, Childe mentally adds. Like hunting down a murderer in a brothel. \r\n\r\n“The fact you can actually convince Ajax to watch opera is impressive enough, Mr. Zhongli.”\r\n\r\n“Hey, I don’t mind watching opera…” Childe mumbles to his father. “I appreciate the arts too.”\r\n\r\nHis mother tidies his hair for the hundredth time tonight and kisses him on the cheek. “Have fun, you two. Mr. Zhongli, please keep him out of trouble.”\r\n\r\nEver the gentleman, Zhongli nods and offers his parents the most charming smile known to all of Teyvat. “I will try.”\r\n\r\nAs soon as they’re out of the house, Childe throws his head back and laughs. “You’re a big liar, consultant; telling my poor parents you’ll keep me out of trouble when you’re taking me out for a night at the brothel.”\r\n\r\nZhongli laughs with him, much quieter but enough to send Childe’s stomach somersaulting in circles. The consultant reaches for his hand, squeezing it, and Childe’s heart joins along with the gymnastics. \r\n\r\n“I believe I told them that I would try,” Zhongli says, completely unaware of the effect he has. “You and I both know it is impossible to keep you out of trouble.”\r\n\r\n \r\n\r\n \r\n\r\nChilde has never been at the Pearl Galley before but he’s heard enough stories to know it’s one of the most extravagant spots in Liyue. Whenever he gazes down at the harbour from his rooftop, he’d see the grandiose ship sailing in the distance, so out of place among Liyue’s calm waters. \r\n\r\nNow that he’s here, he’s not at all surprised by how it looks. It is every bit as gaudy as he expected. He can see why so many of their customers easily spend ridiculous amounts  of Mora on this place. \r\n\r\n“Zhongli!” someone calls. Childe turns around and spots a middle-aged Liyuen man with a goatee, followed by another man whose hairline is receding. He has quite an impressive moustache though. \r\n\r\n“It is good to see you here,” the man with the goatee says to Zhongli, then turns to Childe with obvious curiosity in his eyes. \r\n\r\nZhongli smiles at him and politely bows. “Good evening, Hanxue. This is Ajax. He is my… lover.”\r\n\r\nThe moustached man starts choking. “Lover?!” He coughs, lowering his voice. “Excuse me, I did not mean to yell… I\'m just surprised.”\r\n\r\nYou and everyone else, Childe thinks, resisting the urge to sigh. \r\n\r\n“I heard rumours that our dear consultant was engaged to someone a few days ago, but I didn’t know it was actually real…” the man called Hanxue mutters, narrowing his eyes at Childe. \r\n\r\nChilde fakes his friendliest smile and grabs Zhongli by the hand. “Yes, Zhongli and I are madly in love and we can’t wait to spend the rest of our lives together. Isn’t that right…” He freezes, thinking back to all the cringey pet names his brother Taras used to call one of his girlfriends. “...Babe?” \r\n\r\nZhongli has the courtesy to look amused. “Very much so.”\r\n\r\n“How adorable. It is a pleasure to meet you, Mr. Ajax. I am Hanxue, and this is Yixuan. We are both archeologists; Zhongli often debates with us during our visits here.” Hanxue rubs his chin, still narrowing his eyes at Childe. From the corner of his eyes, he can see Zhongli’s shoulders are tense. “Hmm… Have you been here long, Ajax? I feel as if I have seen you before…”\r\n\r\nChilde quickly shakes his head. “Um, I’m afraid I can’t stay in Liyue often… I visit whenever I can to see Zhongli, but work requires me to be in Snezhnaya a lot…”\r\n\r\n“Yes, perhaps you mistook Ajax for someone else?” Zhongli adds. “There is a rising number of Snezhnayans staying in Liyue these days.”\r\n\r\nThankfully, Hanxue nods, although Childe can tell he’s still trying to remember where he’s seen him before. “That must be it… Oh, I think the opera is starting. Consultant, we have a table already reserved. You and Ajax must join us.”\r\n\r\n“Thank you. We will,” Zhongli says. \r\n\r\nChilde breathes a sigh of relief when the two men leave to sit by their table. Maybe he should have done something to change the colour of his hair for a better disguise; there’s not many gingers walking around Liyue these days after all.\r\n\r\nHe pulls Zhongli close, lowering his voice into a whisper. “I don’t think they believe we’re together.”\r\n\r\n“Hmm. I suppose it is difficult to believe when they have never seen me romantically involved with anyone else,” Zhongli muses. “We will have to be more convincing.”\r\n\r\n“Right…” Childe looks over his shoulder, quickly scanning their surroundings. “See anyone suspicious yet?”\r\n\r\n“It will be easier to spot the potential culprit once the escorts are here… We can gauge their interactions.”\r\n\r\n“Alright, when do they come out?”\r\n\r\nZhongli links his arm around Childe’s and smiles at someone walking past them. “In the Pearl Galley, most prefer to enjoy the opera first. Afterwards, we feast, and that is usually when the escorts grace us with their presence.”\r\n\r\n“And the escorts… They…”\r\n\r\nAs if knowing the course of his thoughts, Zhongli’s eyes soften with amusement and he lets out a quiet laugh. \r\n\r\n“Pursuing sex with an escort here is rare and frowned upon. They are sought for their intellect rather than their bodies,” he explains. “Here, they mostly dance and sing, or recite poetry. It is usually the escort’s decision if she wishes to bed someone, and that person must also be able to afford such a large price.”\r\n\r\nOh. Huh. Childe never knew that. He nods. “You come here a lot…”\r\n\r\nZhongli’s smile widens. “Not for reasons you think. A few have invited me here in the past. It is more for… socialising events